    "id": "3634c4f7-e8ea-41b9-8cf6-0e019bd2a9c4",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu_Marriage_Act,_1955",
    "title": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 – Provisions, Applicability and Key Conditions",
    "summary": "The Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 is a parliamentary statute that codifies and amends Hindu personal law relating to marriage, divorce and related matters. It extends to Hindus, Buddhists, Jains and Sikhs, and to any non‑Muslim, non‑Christian, non‑Parsi, non‑Jew domiciled in India, while also applying to Hindus abroad if domiciled in India. The Act prescribes essential conditions for a valid marriage, including age, monogamy, mental capacity and prohibition of sapindas, and delineates guardianship and registration procedures. Subsequent amendments, notably the Anand Marriage (Amendment) Bill 2012, have refined its scope, while related statutes such as the Special Marriage Act and Section 498A of the IPC address civil marriage and protection of married women.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
