  {
    "id": "2c624f56-4187-4525-8d99-01b11772c919",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_Marriage_Act,_1954",
    "title": "Special Marriage Act, 1954 (India)",
    "summary": "The Special Marriage Act, 1954 provides a secular civil marriage framework for all Indian citizens, irrespective of religion, caste or faith, and also extends to Indian nationals abroad. It replaces the 19th‑century Act III of 1872 and establishes a registration process that requires a notice of intended marriage, a thirty‑day waiting period, and solemnisation before a marriage officer and witnesses. The Act sets uniform conditions such as minimum age (21 for males, 18 for females), monogamy, mental capacity and prohibition of certain relationships, and it subjects succession of property to the Indian Succession Act, with Hindu‑related succession governed by the Hindu Succession Act. Recent judicial scrutiny, notably Supriyo v. Union of India, challenges the notice and objection provisions on constitutional grounds of equality and non‑discrimination.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Special Marriage Act, 1954"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Act III, 1872"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
