        "name": "Supriyo v. Union of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Vaibhav Jain"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Parag Vijay Mehta"
      },
      {
        "type": "entity",
        "name": "Third Law Commission"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Indian Constitution"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Fundamental Rights (Articles 14, 15, 19, 21)"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Purpose",
        "content": "The Act aims to provide a legal framework for the recognition of marriages solemnised outside India involving Indian citizens, whether between two Indians or between an Indian and a foreign national."
      },
      {
        "title": "Judicial Review",
        "content": "The validity of the Act's notice and objection provisions has been challenged in court. In Supriyo v. Union of India, petitioners argued that these provisions infringe constitutional guarantees of equality, non‑discrimination, liberty, and personal autonomy, leading to a Supreme Court hearing that also critiques similar provisions in the Special Marriage Act."
      },
      {
        "title": "Key Provisions",
        "content": "The Act outlines procedures for registration of foreign marriages, defines the role of Indian diplomatic missions, and incorporates safeguards such as notice periods and objections, which have become points of contention in recent litigation."
      }
    ],
