  {
    "id": "050a2824-11c8-49d9-a44a-503c6aebaccc",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protection_of_Women_from_Domestic_Violence_Act,_2005",
    "title": "Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005",
    "summary": "The Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005 (PWDVA) was enacted by the Parliament of India and came into force on 26 October 2006 to provide civil protection to women against domestic violence. For the first time, the Act offers a broad definition of domestic violence, covering physical, sexual, verbal, emotional and economic abuse, as well as dowry‑related harassment. It extends protection beyond marital relationships to include women in live‑in, adopted, blood‑related and other domestic relationships. The law empowers the aggrieved woman to seek protection, residence, monetary, custody and compensation orders, and guarantees free legal aid and shelter home assistance. Implementation is overseen by Protection Officers, with duties also placed on medical facilities and the Ministry of Women and Child Development, though gaps in enforcement persist.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Indian Penal Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 3 (Definition of Domestic Violence)"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 498A (Cruelty by Husband or Relatives)"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "District Court, Mumbai"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Shalu Nigam"
      },
      {
        "type": "government_body",
        "name": "Ministry of Women and Child Development"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Protection Officer"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Aggrieved Person"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Definitions",
        "content": "The Act defines an \"aggrieved person\" as any woman in a domestic relationship who alleges violence, and expands \"domestic violence\" under Section 3 to include physical, sexual, verbal, emotional and economic abuse, as well as dowry‑related harassment and threats."
      },
      {
        "title": "Scope",
        "content": "Protection is available to women in marital, live‑in, adopted, blood‑related and other domestic relationships, covering actual abuse or threats, and includes women residing with relatives such as sisters, widows or mothers."
      },
      {
        "title": "Rights of the Aggrieved Person",
        "content": "Under Chapter III, the aggrieved woman may apply for protection, monetary relief, custody, residence and compensation orders; obtain free legal services; and file criminal complaints under Section 498A of the IPC."
      },
      {
        "title": "Shelter Homes",
        "content": "The Act mandates that each State or Union Territory, through the Ministry of Women and Child Development, identify and notify shelter homes, and allows Protection Officers or service providers to secure shelter for the aggrieved person."
      },
      {
        "title": "Medical Facilities",
        "content": "Medical establishments must provide free medical aid to the aggrieved woman irrespective of any prior direction from a Protection Officer, ensuring health support independent of other relief mechanisms."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implementation",
        "content": "Despite the framework, implementation gaps persist, as highlighted by experts such as Shalu Nigam and observations of courts, indicating challenges in enforcement, awareness, and resource allocation."
      }
    ],
