      "ICMR guidelines",
      "National Guidelines"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "dfbc4532-20c4-42b1-9a66-1c2363ee2149",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_Civil_Code",
    "title": "Uniform Civil Code – proposal for a common personal law in India",
    "summary": "The Uniform Civil Code (UCC) seeks to replace religion‑based personal laws with a single set of statutes governing marriage, divorce, inheritance, adoption and maintenance for all Indian citizens. While Articles 25‑28 of the Constitution protect religious freedom, Article 44 instructs the State to pursue a uniform civil code as a directive principle. Historically, personal laws were codified for Hindus and Muslims during the British Raj, with Goa being the only state to have a common family law until 2024. The issue gained prominence after the 1985 Shah Bano case and has seen multiple legislative attempts, most recently under the BJP‑RSS alliance, but faces opposition from opposition parties and tribal groups. Implementation remains under debate, with political, constitutional, and social dimensions shaping the discourse.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "constitution_article",
        "name": "Article 25"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution_article",
        "name": "Article 26"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution_article",
        "name": "Article 27"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution_article",
        "name": "Article 28"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution_article",
        "name": "Article 44"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Uniform Civil Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "legislation",
        "name": "Hindu Code Bills"
      },
      {
        "type": "case",
        "name": "Shah Bano case (1985)"
      },
      {
        "type": "state",
        "name": "Goa Civil Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "political_party",
        "name": "Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)"
      },
      {
        "type": "political_organization",
        "name": "Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh (RSS)"
      },
      {
        "type": "political_alliance",
        "name": "National Democratic Alliance (NDA)"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Prime Minister Narendra Modi"
      },
      {
        "type": "report",
        "name": "Lex Loci Report (1840)"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Definition and Scope",
        "content": "The UCC proposes a single set of personal laws applicable to all citizens irrespective of religion, covering marriage, divorce, maintenance, inheritance, adoption and succession."
      },
      {
        "title": "Constitutional Basis",
        "content": "Articles 25‑28 guarantee freedom of religion and the right of communities to manage their own affairs, while Article 44, a Directive Principle, directs the State to secure a uniform civil code for all citizens."
      },
      {
        "title": "Historical Background",
        "content": "Personal laws were first codified during the British Raj for Hindus and Muslims. Goa retained a common family law (Goa Civil Code) from Portuguese rule, making it the sole state with a uniform code prior to 2024. Post‑independence, the Hindu Code Bills reformed Hindu personal law but left Christians, Jews, Muslims and Parsis untouched."
      },
      {
        "title": "Key Judicial Milestones",
        "content": "The 1985 Shah Bano case highlighted gender inequities in Muslim personal law and sparked nationwide debate on the need for a common law framework."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legislative Attempts",
        "content": "A UCC bill was introduced twice (Nov 2019 and Mar 2020) but withdrawn before parliamentary debate. Current discussions involve the BJP and RSS, with proposals reportedly under consideration."
      },
      {
        "title": "Political and Social Opposition",
        "content": "Opposition parties, many NDA allies, and tribal groups in Northeast India contest the UCC, arguing it threatens religious freedom, cultural diversity, and special tribal privileges."
      },
      {
        "title": "Current Status (as of 2023‑2024)",
        "content": "Prime Minister Narendra Modi reaffirmed the government's commitment to a UCC in June 2023, but no legislation has been tabled. The issue remains a contentious political subject with ongoing consultations."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Uniform Civil Code",
      "personal law",
      "religious freedom",
      "Article 44",
      "Directive Principles",
      "Hindu Code Bills",
      "Shah Bano case",
      "Muslim personal law",
      "Sharia",
      "Goa Civil Code",
      "inheritance",
      "marriage",
      "divorce",
      "adoption",
      "maintenance"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "7298cf08-6648-4ce8-951c-0b2cb625ae7d",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triple_talaq_in_India",
    "title": "Abolition of Triple Talaq in India: Judicial and Legislative Milestones",
    "summary": "Triple talaq, an instant Islamic divorce where a Muslim man pronounces \"talaq\" three times in one sitting, was historically permitted in India but faced intense scrutiny for violating gender equality and constitutional principles. In August 2017, a five‑judge bench of the Supreme Court held the practice unconstitutional, though the decision was split 3‑2. The Parliament subsequently enacted the Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Marriage) Act, 2019, criminalising instant triple talaq and providing maintenance rights to divorced women. The legislation passed after extensive parliamentary debate and reflects broader debates on a Uniform Civil Code under Article 44 of the Constitution. The ban aligns India with a growing number of countries that have prohibited the practice.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "The Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Marriage) Act, 2019"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Ishrat Jahan"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Arif Mohammad Khan"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Triple talaq (talaq-e-biddat)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Talaq-e-Hasan"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Khula"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Uniform Civil Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "article",
        "name": "Article 44 of the Indian Constitution"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Judgment (22 August 2017)",
        "content": "A five‑judge bench examined the constitutionality of instant triple talaq. Three judges held it unconstitutional as arbitrary and violative of fundamental rights, while two judges dissented, finding it within personal law. The Court declared pronouncements of triple talaq in a single sitting void and illegal, prompting legislative action."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legislative Ban – Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Marriage) Act, 2019",
        "content": "Enacted on 30 July 2019, the Act criminalises instant triple talaq (spoken, written, or electronic) with a maximum imprisonment of three years. It declares such divorces void, entitles the aggrieved wife to maintenance for herself and dependent children, and makes the practice illegal from 1 August 2019, superseding the 2019 ordinance."
      },
      {
        "title": "Parliamentary Proceedings",
        "content": "The bill was first introduced on 22 August 2017, faced opposition from several parties, and was passed by the Lok Sabha on 28 December 2017. After a prolonged debate, the Rajya Sabha approved it on 30 July 2019 (99‑84). Prominent supporters included petitioner Ishrat Jahan and former Union Minister Arif Mohammad Khan."
      },
      {
        "title": "Permissible Islamic Divorce Mechanisms",
        "content": "The Supreme Court recognised \"Talaq-e-Hasan\" (one pronouncement per month over three months) and \"Khula\" (mutual divorce) as constitutionally permissible. Traditional waiting periods (iddat) and the concept of \"Nikah Halala\"—remarriage to another man before returning to the former husband—remain part of personal law but are distinct from the banned instant talaq."
      },
      {
        "title": "International Context",
        "content": "India joins Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and 20 other nations that have outlawed instant triple talaq, reflecting a global trend towards safeguarding women's rights within Muslim personal law."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "triple talaq",
      "instant divorce",
      "constitutional challenge",
      "Supreme Court of India",
      "Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Marriage) Act",
      "uniform civil code",
      "article 44",
      "gender equality",
      "maintenance",
      "iddat",
      "khula",
      "talaq-e-Hasan",
      "criminalisation",
      "personal law"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "68ca22e6-8fbf-486f-b9e5-07ea64802e82",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahr",
    "title": "Mahr as a Mandatory Bride‑Wealth Obligation under Muslim Personal Law",
    "summary": "Mahr is a compulsory payment by the groom to the bride, stipulated in the Islamic marriage contract and recognised as the bride's exclusive property. Unlike dower or dowry, mahr is legally required for every Muslim marriage and must be specified at the time of nikah, though payment may be deferred. The amount can be paid immediately (mu‘ajjal) and/or promised for later (mu’ajjal), and courts enforce an equitable sum when the contract lacks a precise figure. Mahr underpins the financial independence of Muslim women and is governed by Quranic injunctions, hadith, and the interpretive rules of various fiqh schools, which Indian courts apply within the framework of Muslim personal law.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Mahr"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Mu‘ajjal (prompt mahr)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Mu’ajjal (deferred mahr)"
      },
      {
        "type": "religious_text",
        "name": "Quran"
      },
      {
        "type": "religious_text",
        "name": "Hadith"
      },
      {
        "type": "law",
        "name": "Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act, 1937"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisprudence",
        "name": "Fiqh (Islamic jurisprudence)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Bridewealth"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Dower"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Dowry"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Definition and Legal Significance",
        "content": "Mahr is defined as the bride's wealth right, payable by the groom in money, property, or other agreed items, and becomes the bride's exclusive property upon marriage."
      },
      {
        "title": "Distinction from Dower and Dowry",
        "content": "Mahr differs from Western dower (a post‑mortem provision) and dowry (a transfer from the bride’s family) because it is mandatory for every Islamic marriage and must be stipulated at the time of the contract."
      },
      {
        "title": "Specification in the Marriage Contract",
        "content": "The marriage contract (nikah) must contain a clear mahr amount. If the contract lacks a precise figure, the husband is still obligated to pay an equitable sum determined by the court."
      },
      {
        "title": "Payment Structure: Mu‘ajjal and Mu’ajjal",
        "content": "Mahr can be divided into an immediate portion (mu‘ajjal) paid at nikah and a deferred portion (mu’ajjal) promised for later, often larger, payment after consummation."
      },
      {
        "title": "Regional Fi­qh Variations and Enforceability",
        "content": "Interpretations of mahr, its amount, and conditions of enforceability vary among the Hanafi, Shafi'i, Maliki, and Hanbali schools, which Indian courts consider when adjudicating disputes under Muslim personal law."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "mahr",
      "mu‘ajjal",
      "mu’ajjal",
      "Islamic marriage contract",
      "Muslim personal law",
      "fiqh",
      "Quranic injunction",
      "financial independence of wife",
      "bridewealth",
      "dower",
      "dowry",
      "equitable sum",
      "Islamic family law",
      "legal obligation"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "2ba73fa4-e373-4c5b-a204-491c68e8a654",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygamy_in_India",
    "title": "Legal Status of Polygamy in India",
    "summary": "In India, polygamy is prohibited for Hindus, Sikhs, Jains, and Buddhists under the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955, which mandates monogamous marriage. Muslim personal law permits a man to have up to four wives, subject to the condition of equal treatment, but polyandry is not permitted for any community. The Indian Constitution's Directive Principle (Article 44) advocates a uniform civil code and the abolition of practices inimical to equality, influencing debates on reform. Criminal provisions under the Indian Penal Code penalise bigamy for those who contract a second marriage while the first is subsisting, unless exempted by personal law. Judicial pronouncements, notably by the Supreme Court, have upheld the constitutionality of existing personal law exceptions while urging reform towards gender equality.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Indian Penal Code, 1860"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act, 1937"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution",
        "name": "Article 44, Directive Principles of State Policy"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
