      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Bigamy"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Uniform Civil Code"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Monogamy under Hindu Law",
        "content": "The Hindu Marriage Act, 1955, applies to Hindus, Sikhs, Jains and Buddhists and declares a marriage void if either party has a living spouse, thereby enforcing monogamy."
      },
      {
        "title": "Polygyny under Muslim Personal Law",
        "content": "Islamic personal law in India allows a Muslim man to marry up to four women simultaneously, provided he can treat them equitably. This exception is preserved by the Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act, 1937."
      },
      {
        "title": "Criminal Provisions on Bigamy",
        "content": "Section 494 of the Indian Penal Code prescribes imprisonment for anyone who contracts a second marriage while the first subsists, unless the second marriage is permissible under personal law."
      },
      {
        "title": "Constitutional and Policy Context",
        "content": "Article 44 of the Constitution urges the State to enact a Uniform Civil Code, aiming to eliminate practices like polygamy that are inconsistent with gender equality, though no comprehensive code has yet been enacted."
      },
      {
        "title": "Judicial Interpretation and Recent Developments",
        "content": "The Supreme Court has upheld the validity of Muslim polygamy while emphasizing the need for reform, and lower courts have occasionally struck down bigamous marriages that violate the Hindu Marriage Act."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
