  {
    "id": "cb0725df-09d1-4285-a88e-00d5247b2034",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bigamy",
    "title": "Bigamy under Indian Family Law",
    "summary": "Bigamy in India is the act of marrying a second person while the first marriage remains legally subsisting. Under the Indian Penal Code, Section 494 criminalises bigamy and stipulates imprisonment of up to ten years for non‑Muslim individuals. An exception exists for Muslim men, for whom a second marriage is permissible under Muslim personal law provided the first wife consents, although the practice is rare. The state of Goa, governed by its own civil code, allows Hindus to contract a second marriage under specific circumstances. The law treats a marriage as subsisting until a divorce is finalised, and de‑facto separations do not alter marital status.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Indian Penal Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 494 (bigamy)"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Muslim Personal Law (Shariat) Application Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisdiction",
        "name": "Goa Civil Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Monogamy"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Polygamy"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Muslim men"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Definition and General Rule",
        "content": "Bigamy is defined as entering into a marriage while a prior marriage is still valid under Indian law. A person remains married until a divorce decree becomes final; mere separation does not affect status."
      },
      {
        "title": "Criminalisation under the Indian Penal Code",
        "content": "Section 494 of the IPC declares bigamy a punishable offence, prescribing imprisonment up to ten years and/or fine for persons who contract a second marriage without lawful dissolution of the first."
      },
      {
        "title": "Exception for Muslim Men",
        "content": "Muslim personal law permits a Muslim man to contract a second marriage if the first wife gives her consent, making the second marriage valid under that personal law, though it remains void under the secular IPC for non‑Muslims."
      },
      {
        "title": "Special Provision for Goa",
        "content": "The Goa Civil Code, a uniform family law for the state, allows Hindus to contract a second marriage under certain conditions, diverging from the general prohibition applicable elsewhere in India."
      },
      {
        "title": "Enforcement and Judicial Practice",
        "content": "Indian courts, including the Supreme Court, have upheld the IPC's stance on bigamy while recognising the limited personal‑law exception; prosecutions are relatively infrequent, especially for Muslim‑law marriages."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
