  {
    "id": "06e25e7c-7e40-4cad-bc8f-d78c43c9acbc",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Restitution_of_conjugal_rights",
    "title": "Restitution of Conjugal Rights – Historical Development and Abolition in Common Law Jurisdictions",
    "summary": "Restitution of conjugal rights was an equitable remedy that allowed a deserted spouse to compel the other to resume cohabitation, originally enforced by the ecclesiastical courts in England. Over the 19th and 20th centuries, a series of statutes modified the remedy, gradually reducing its punitive aspects and linking non‑compliance to judicial separation and financial orders. By the late 20th century the action was deemed obsolete and was abolished in England and Wales by the Matrimonial Proceedings and Property Act 1970, with similar reforms enacted in Scotland, Ireland, Australia and other common‑law jurisdictions.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Ecclesiastical Courts Act 1813"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Matrimonial Causes Act 1884"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Matrimonial Causes Act 1923"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Supreme Court of Judicature (Consolidation) Act 1925"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Matrimonial Proceedings and Property Act 1970"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Law Reform (Husband and Wife) (Scotland) Act 1984"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Family Law Act 1988 (Ireland)"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Family Law Act 1975 (Cth)"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Ecclesiastical Courts"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Court for Divorce and Matrimonial Causes"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "desertion"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "judicial separation"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "divorce"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisdiction",
        "name": "United Kingdom"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisdiction",
        "name": "Scotland"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisdiction",
        "name": "Ireland"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisdiction",
        "name": "Australia"
      },
      {
        "type": "jurisdiction",
        "name": "South Africa"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Historical Origin",
        "content": "The remedy originated in English ecclesiastical courts, where a spouse could petition for a decree of restitution of conjugal rights against a partner living apart without justification. Non‑compliance originally attracted excommunication, later replaced by imprisonment."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legislative Modifications in England and Wales",
        "content": "Key statutes reshaped the remedy: the Ecclesiastical Courts Act 1813 limited punishment to imprisonment; the Matrimonial Causes Act 1884 linked non‑compliance to statutory desertion and allowed judicial separation; the Matrimonial Causes Act 1923 equalised divorce grounds, reducing reliance on restitution orders; the Supreme Court of Judicature (Consolidation) Act 1925 repealed earlier provisions but retained the right to use the order as a ground for separation and financial orders."
      },
      {
        "title": "Abolition in England and Wales",
        "content": "A 1969 Law Commission report recommended repeal, and the action was formally abolished by the Matrimonial Proceedings and Property Act 1970, reflecting its obsolescence and rare usage."
      },
      {
        "title": "Abolition in Other Common‑Law Jurisdictions",
        "content": "Scotland abolished the analogous 'adherence' action via the Law Reform (Husband and Wife) (Scotland) Act 1984. Ireland eliminated the remedy through the Family Law Act 1988. Australia removed it in the Family Law Act 1975, though a residual provision (Section 114(2)) remains controversially on the books."
      },
      {
        "title": "Contemporary Issues",
        "content": "In Australia, the lingering statutory wording permitting orders to relieve a party from conjugal obligations is criticized for contradicting modern principles of marital consent and gender equality, with law reform bodies urging its repeal."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "restitution of conjugal rights",
      "desertion",
      "ecclesiastical courts",
