      "marital obligations",
      "legal abolition",
      "common law jurisdictions",
      "Matrimonial Proceedings and Property Act 1970",
      "Law Reform (Scotland) Act 1984",
      "Family Law Act 1975"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "999db4dd-74a6-4e05-94e8-0a1e653fafcc",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Void_marriage",
    "title": "Void Marriage – Legal Definition, Effects and Grounds",
    "summary": "A void marriage is one that is considered null and void from its inception and is treated by law as if it never existed. It differs from a voidable marriage, which remains valid until annulled by a court at the election of a party. If a void marriage is entered in good faith, the spouses may be recognised as putative spouses, receiving limited rights despite the marriage’s invalidity. Grounds for a void marriage typically include prohibited consanguinity, existing marriages (bigamy), lack of legal capacity, and statutory prohibitions such as same‑sex or group marriages. Jurisdictions vary on whether a formal annulment is required to remove any impediment to remarriage.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Paul J. Goda"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Marriage Act 1949 (England and Wales)"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Matrimonial Causes Act 1973"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Divorce (Religious Marriages) Act 2002"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Family Code (Philippines)"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Domestic Relations Law (New York)"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "civil courts"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "ecclesiastical courts"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "void marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "voidable marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "putative marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "annulment"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "consanguinity"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "bigamy"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "History",
        "content": "The distinction between void and voidable marriages emerged from historic jurisdictional conflicts between civil courts, which handled property, and ecclesiastical courts, which oversaw marriage validity. The Reformation shifted marriage from a primarily religious sacrament to a civil contract, solidifying the legal categories. Early American jurisprudence mirrored this split, classifying civil disabilities as grounds for void marriages and canonical disabilities as grounds for voidable marriages."
      },
      {
        "title": "Generally",
        "content": "A marriage is deemed void when it violates statutory or public‑policy restrictions such as close consanguinity, existing marriage (bigamy), lack of legal capacity (e.g., age or civil rights loss), or prohibited forms like same‑sex or group marriages. Void marriages are treated as never having existed, though some jurisdictions still require a formal annulment to clear impediments to remarriage. Conversely, a voidable marriage remains valid until annulled by a court decision."
      },
      {
        "title": "By jurisdiction – England and Wales",
        "content": "Under English law, a void marriage is one that ‘never took place’, governed by sections 11‑16 of the Matrimonial Causes Act 1973 and later amendments. Grounds include prohibited consanguinity, a party being under sixteen, or an existing lawful marriage at the time of the ceremony."
      },
      {
        "title": "By jurisdiction – Philippines",
        "content": "The Philippine Family Code declares marriages void ab initio when essential requisites (legal capacity and consent) or formal requisites (valid license, solemnizing officer, ceremony) are absent. Additional grounds mirror those in other jurisdictions, such as bigamy, polygamy, psychological incapacity, and incest."
      },
      {
        "title": "By jurisdiction – United States (New York)",
        "content": "New York’s Domestic Relations Law makes incestuous marriages void, defining incest to include ancestor‑descendant, brother‑sister (whole or half blood), and uncle‑niece/aunt‑nephew relationships, while cousin marriages remain permissible."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "void marriage",
      "nullity",
      "annulment",
      "consanguinity",
      "bigamy",
      "putative marriage",
      "civil capacity",
      "legal requisites",
      "jurisdiction",
      "family law",
      "incest",
      "same‑sex marriage",
      "group marriage"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "e6f50648-f9b3-49d4-8e35-800bb93b8b4a",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voidable_marriage",
    "title": "Voidable Marriage under Indian Family Law",
    "summary": "A voidable marriage is a legally valid marriage that may be cancelled at the option of one of the parties through an annulment suit. It differs from a void marriage, which is invalid ab initio and produces no legal effect. Grounds for a marriage to be declared voidable include lack of genuine consent due to duress, mistake, intoxication, or mental defect. Only a living party to the marriage may seek annulment; the remedy is unavailable after the death of either spouse. Historically, the concept evolved from ecclesiastical courts and was later incorporated into civil jurisprudence concerning property and matrimonial rights.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Voidable marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Void marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Annulment"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Duress"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Mistake"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Intoxication"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Mental defect"
      },
      {
        "type": "institution",
        "name": "Ecclesiastical courts"
      },
      {
        "type": "institution",
        "name": "Civil courts"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Impotence"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Definition",
        "content": "A voidable marriage is a marriage that remains legally valid until it is annulled at the discretion of one of the spouses."
      },
      {
        "title": "Distinction from Void Marriage",
        "content": "Unlike a void marriage, which is unlawful from its inception and produces no legal rights, a voidable marriage produces enforceable rights until it is set aside by a court."
      },
      {
        "title": "Grounds for Voidability",
        "content": "The marriage may be annulled if consent was compromised by duress, mistake, intoxication, or a mental defect that rendered the party incapable of understanding the marriage."
      },
      {
        "title": "Procedure and Limitation",
        "content": "Only a living party may file an annulment suit; the remedy is barred after the death of either spouse, and the action must be brought before a civil court with jurisdiction over family matters."
      },
      {
        "title": "Historical Background",
        "content": "The doctrine originated in early ecclesiastical courts that adjudicated matrimonial validity and was later assimilated into civil law to address property and marital rights."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "voidable marriage",
      "annulment",
      "consent",
      "duress",
      "mistake",
      "intoxication",
