      "statutory reform",
      "gender bias"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "e89a2d9b-89cf-45e6-9ea4-9fb2d9c30560",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lok_Adalat",
    "title": "Lok Adalat – Statutory Alternative Dispute Resolution Mechanism in India",
    "summary": "Lok Adalat, created under the Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987, provides an alternative mechanism for resolving civil, family and certain criminal disputes outside conventional courts. Awards rendered by Lok Adalats are deemed civil court decrees, final and binding, with no right of appeal, though aggrieved parties may initiate fresh litigation. Various forms—Permanent, National, Mega and Mobile Lok Adalats—operate at national, state, district and taluk levels, handling pre‑litigation and pending cases including matrimonial, property and monetary disputes. The conciliators act only as facilitators, and procedural strictness of the Evidence Act and Civil Procedure Code is relaxed, allowing quicker settlements.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "Act",
        "name": "Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987"
      },
      {
        "type": "Authority",
        "name": "National Legal Services Authority (NALSA)"
      },
      {
        "type": "Authority",
        "name": "State Legal Services Authority"
      },
      {
        "type": "Court",
        "name": "High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "Court",
        "name": "District Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "Court",
        "name": "Taluk Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Permanent Lok Adalat (PLA)"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "National Lok Adalat"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Mega Lok Adalat"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Mobile Lok Adalat"
      },
      {
        "type": "Act",
        "name": "Negotiable Instruments Act (Section 138)"
      },
      {
        "type": "Act",
        "name": "Indian Motor Vehicles Act, 1988"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Public Utility Services (PUS)"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Compoundable offences"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Pre‑litigation settlement"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Award enforcement"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Statutory Basis",
        "content": "Lok Adalat derives its authority from the Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987, which grants it the status of a statutory body for alternative dispute resolution. Section 22A defines ‘Public Utility Services’, and Section 22B empowers the creation of Permanent Lok Adalats to adjudicate matters relating to those services."
      },
      {
        "title": "Structure and Types",
        "content": "Lok Adalats function at four hierarchical levels—National, State, District and Taluk. The system includes Permanent, National, Mega and Mobile Lok Adalats, each designed to address specific categories of disputes, ranging from public utility cases to large‑scale batch settlements."
      },
      {
        "title": "Jurisdiction and Eligible Cases",
        "content": "Both pending court cases and pre‑litigation matters that are civil, matrimonial, property or compoundable criminal in nature may be referred to Lok Adalat. Specific examples include disputes under Section 138 of the Negotiable Instruments Act, recovery of money, labour matters, utility bills, and family/matrimonial issues."
      },
      {
        "title": "Procedural Features",
        "content": "The conciliators act as statutory conciliators, not judges, and may employ counseling to achieve settlement. No court fee is charged, and any fee paid earlier is refunded upon settlement. Formal procedural codes and the Evidence Act are applied loosely to facilitate compromise."
      },
      {
        "title": "Binding Nature of Awards",
        "content": "Awards pronounced by Lok Adalat are deemed to be civil court decrees, final and binding on the parties. No appeal lies against the award, although aggrieved parties retain the right to initiate independent litigation. The award is executable like any court decree."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Lok Adalat",
      "Alternative Dispute Resolution",
      "Legal Services Authorities Act",
      "Permanent Lok Adalat",
