      "NALSA",
      "Court fee refund",
      "Conciliators"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "8c77cb4b-7b98-4840-ae9c-1f74303f0d2b",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_Services_Authorities_Act,_1987",
    "title": "Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987 – Free Legal Aid Framework",
    "summary": "The Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987 operationalises Article 39‑A of the Constitution, guaranteeing free legal aid to economically weaker sections of society. It establishes the National Legal Services Authority (NALSA) and a network of Legal Services Authorities at state and district levels to provide legal assistance, representation and advice. The Act specifies categories of persons entitled to aid, including scheduled castes and tribes, women, children, victims of rape, disability, and disaster victims. It also confers finality on Lok Adalat awards, prohibiting appeals against them. The Act came into force on 9 November 1987, and 9 November is observed annually as National Legal Services Day.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Legal Services Authorities Act, 1987"
      },
      {
        "type": "authority",
        "name": "National Legal Services Authority (NALSA)"
      },
      {
        "type": "article",
        "name": "Article 39‑A, Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Lok Adalat"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Free legal aid"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Legal aid eligibility"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "National Legal Services Day"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Purpose and Constitutional Basis",
        "content": "The Act gives effect to Article 39‑A, which mandates the State to provide free legal aid to ensure equality before the law and promote justice for the poor and marginalized."
      },
      {
        "title": "Establishment of NALSA and State/District Authorities",
        "content": "It creates the National Legal Services Authority (NALSA) as the apex body, along with State Legal Services Authorities (SLSAs) and District Legal Services Authorities (DLSAs) to administer legal aid across India."
      },
      {
        "title": "Persons Entitled to Legal Aid (Section 12)",
        "content": "Eligibility extends to scheduled castes/tribes, beggars, victims of human trafficking, children, women (including rape victims), persons with disabilities, disaster victims, industrial workmen, and individuals with income below prescribed limits."
      },
      {
        "title": "Scope of Legal Services",
        "content": "The Act covers representation by advocates, preparation of pleadings, drafting of special leave petitions, payment of court fees, translation, and advisory services in civil and criminal matters."
      },
      {
        "title": "Finality of Lok Adalat Awards",
        "content": "Awards passed by Lok Adalats are deemed final and binding; no appeal lies to any higher court against such awards."
      },
      {
        "title": "Commemoration",
        "content": "9 November is observed annually as National Legal Services Day to mark the Act’s commencement."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Legal aid",
      "Article 39-A",
      "NALSA",
      "Lok Adalat",
      "Free legal representation",
      "Eligibility criteria",
      "Scheduled Castes",
      "Scheduled Tribes",
      "Women’s rights",
      "Child rights",
      "Disability",
      "National Legal Services Day",
      "Legal Services Authorities"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "74f48283-3f6a-4dc5-aff0-d6425c2c821f",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_Commission_of_India",
    "title": "Law Commission of India: History, Structure and Functions",
    "summary": "The Law Commission of India is an executive advisory body established by Government order to research and recommend legal reforms, reporting to the Ministry of Law and Justice. Originating in 1833 under the Charter Act during British rule, it evolved through several pre‑independence commissions that contributed to the Indian Penal Code, Criminal Procedure Code, Evidence Act and Contract Act. Since independence, the first commission was set up in 1955 and, to date, twenty‑three commissions have been constituted, each chaired by a senior jurist and serving a fixed three‑year term. The commission presently consists of a retired judge as chairperson and a panel of legal scholars, tasked with advising on reforms across all branches of law, including family law matters.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Lord Macaulay"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "M. C. Setalvad"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice T. V. Venkatarama Aiyar"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice J. L. Kapur"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Rituraj Awasthi"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Indian Penal Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Criminal Procedure Code (1898)"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Indian Evidence Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Indian Contract Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "institution",
        "name": "Ministry of Law and Justice"
      },
      {
        "type": "institution",
        "name": "Law Commission of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "legal reform"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "advisory body"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Establishment and Mandate",
        "content": "The Law Commission is created by a Government order, functions as an executive body, and advises the Ministry of Law and Justice on legal reforms. Its members are senior legal experts, usually retired judges, appointed for a fixed three‑year tenure."
      },
      {
        "title": "Historical Evolution",
        "content": "The first commission was instituted under the Charter Act of 1833 to unify dual legal systems applied to British subjects and local inhabitants. Subsequent colonial commissions contributed to major statutes such as the IPC, CrPC, Evidence Act, and Contract Act."
      },
      {
        "title": "Pre‑Independence Commissions",
        "content": "Four commissions were established between 1834 and the early 20th century, influencing foundational legislation still in force. A two‑member Viceroy's Executive Council also supported these efforts."
      },
      {
        "title": "Post‑Independence Commissions",
        "content": "The first post‑independence commission was set up in 1955 under M. C. Setalvad, establishing the three‑year term convention. Twenty‑two additional commissions have followed, each producing reports that shape contemporary statutes."
      },
      {
        "title": "Current Composition (22nd Commission)",
        "content": "Appointed on 7 November 2022, the 22nd Law Commission is chaired by Justice Rituraj Awasthi, with members Justice KT Sankaran, Prof. Anand Paliwal, Prof. DP Verma, Prof. Raka Arya, and Shri M. Karunanithi."
      },
      {
        "title": "Functions and Areas of Focus",
        "content": "The Commission undertakes detailed research, drafts model bills, and recommends amendments across civil, criminal, and family law. Its advice informs parliamentary legislation and judicial reform initiatives."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
