  {
    "id": "4d1d54cd-4977-4a68-a89b-43bf0c3657c7",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/divorced-muslim-woman-can-seek-maintenance-from-husband-under-s125-crpc-supreme-court-262843",
    "title": "Supreme Court Rules Divorced Muslim Women Entitled to Maintenance Under Section 125 CrPC",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court held that a divorced Muslim woman is eligible to claim maintenance from her former husband under Section 125 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973, despite personal law provisions that traditionally restrict such claims. The Court clarified that the right to maintenance is a fundamental right under Article 21 of the Constitution and cannot be denied on the basis of religion. It emphasized that the provision of Section 125 is a secular remedial measure applicable to all persons irrespective of personal law. The judgment sets a precedent for uniform application of maintenance rights across all communities and directs courts to enforce this right without prejudice. The decision also outlines procedural safeguards for filing and determining maintenance claims by divorced Muslim women.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "statute",
        "name": "Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 125 CrPC"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution",
        "name": "Article 21, Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "community",
        "name": "Muslim women"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Divorced husband"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background and Legal Issue",
        "content": "The case arose from a petition filed by a divorced Muslim woman seeking maintenance from her former husband. The contention was whether Section 125 CrPC, which provides for maintenance to wives, children, and parents, could be invoked by a Muslim woman after divorce, given the provisions of Muslim personal law."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Holding",
        "content": "The Court held that Section 125 CrPC is a secular provision that supersedes personal law where the right to life and dignity is concerned. Consequently, a divorced Muslim woman is entitled to claim maintenance under this section."
      },
      {
        "title": "Rationale and Constitutional Basis",
        "content": "The judgment rested on the interpretation of Article 21, which guarantees the right to life and personal liberty, and the principle that the state must not discriminate on the basis of religion while enforcing statutory rights."
      },
      {
        "title": "Procedural Implications",
        "content": "Courts are directed to accept maintenance applications from divorced Muslim women under Section 125 CrPC, assess the husband's liability based on his means, and award appropriate maintenance without requiring ancillary proof of dower (mahr) or other personal law concepts."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact and Future Outlook",
        "content": "The decision promotes uniformity in the application of maintenance law across religious communities and strengthens the protective ambit of the Constitution for vulnerable spouses."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Section 125 CrPC",
      "maintenance",
      "Divorced Muslim woman",
      "Supreme Court",
      "Personal law",
      "Constitutional law",
      "Article 21",
      "Family law",
      "Husband's liability",
      "Gender justice",
      "Legal uniformity",
      "Secular provision",
      "Right to life"
    ]
  },
