  {
    "id": "6b08311b-221a-47ba-9206-1a823fc9df20",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-declaration-of-right-to-marry-necessary-to-end-stigma-against-lgbtqia-community-mukul-rohatgi-argues-in-supreme-court-226670",
    "title": "Mukul Rohatgi urges Supreme Court to declare right to marry for LGBTQIA+ community",
    "summary": "During the Supreme Court hearing on marriage equality, senior counsel Mukul Rohatgi contended that a clear constitutional declaration affirming the right of LGBTQIA+ individuals to marry is essential to eradicate stigma and provide legal recognition. He highlighted that while Section 377 has been struck down, the absence of a marriage right perpetuates discrimination. Rohatgi relied on Articles 14, 15(1)(a), 21 and 25 of the Indian Constitution, arguing that the right to marry is an integral facet of the right to life and personal liberty. He urged the Court to extend the constitutional safeguards to include same‑sex marriage, thereby aligning Indian law with international human‑rights standards. The argument underscores the need for affirmative jurisprudence to address societal prejudice and ensure equality before law.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Mukul Rohatgi"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "legislation",
        "name": "Indian Constitution"
      },
      {
        "type": "legislation",
        "name": "Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "LGBTQIA+ rights"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Right to marry"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Stigma"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background of the Marriage Equality Litigation",
        "content": "The case follows the Supreme Court's 2018 judgment that decriminalised consensual homosexual acts by striking down Section 377. Despite this, same‑sex couples remain unable to legally marry, prompting a fresh petition seeking a constitutional guarantee of marriage rights for LGBTQIA+ persons."
      },
      {
        "title": "Arguments Advanced by Mukul Rohatgi",
        "content": "Rohatgi argued that denying marriage rights perpetuates social stigma and violates the equality clause (Article 14), non‑discrimination clause (Article 15(1)(a)), and the right to life and personal liberty (Article 21). He contended that marriage is a fundamental aspect of dignity and personal autonomy, and its denial is a form of discrimination prohibited by the Constitution."
      },
      {
        "title": "Constitutional Provisions Cited",
        "content": "Articles 14, 15(1)(a), 21, 25 (freedom of conscience and religion) and 19(1)(g) (right to practice any profession, trade or business) were invoked to establish the legal basis for extending marriage rights to same‑sex couples."
      },
      {
        "title": "Potential Implications of a Positive Declaration",
        "content": "A judicial pronouncement affirming the right to marry would compel legislative amendment of personal laws, enable same‑sex couples to avail marriage-related benefits, and serve as a landmark step toward eradicating societal prejudice against the LGBTQIA+ community."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
