      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Non-Discrimination"
      },
      {
        "type": "procedure",
        "name": "Review Petition"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background of the Marriage Equality Judgment",
        "content": "In 2018, the Supreme Court, by a five‑judge Constitution Bench, read down Section 377 of the IPC, decriminalising consensual homosexual acts and affirming that the Constitution guarantees the right to marry irrespective of sexual orientation."
      },
      {
        "title": "Filing of Review Petitions",
        "content": "Following the 2018 decision, a group of petitioners filed review petitions seeking to overturn the judgment on grounds of alleged judicial overreach and procedural impropriety."
      },
      {
        "title": "Justice Sanjiv Khanna’s Recusal",
        "content": "Justice Khanna, who participated in the original 2018 bench, recused himself from hearing the review petitions, stating that his prior involvement could give rise to an impression of bias."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications for the Bench and Proceedings",
        "content": "The recusal leaves the remaining judges – Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud and Justice Chandramouli Kr. Prasad – to hear the matters, raising questions about quorum, bench composition and the interpretation of Article 136 powers for review."
      },
      {
        "title": "Potential Outcomes and Impact on Family Law",
        "content": "If the review petitions succeed, it could reverse the recognition of marriage equality, affecting same‑sex couples’ rights to marriage, adoption, and inheritance under personal laws."
      }
    ],
