  {
    "id": "b342764c-5927-48ef-8037-5b1a4a37ab67",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-under-special-marriage-act-can-be-registered-through-video-conferencing-supreme-court-179190",
    "title": "Supreme Court Allows Video‑Conferencing Registration of Special Marriage Act Marriages",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India, in response to the challenges posed by the COVID‑19 pandemic, ruled that marriages solemnised under the Special Marriage Act, 1954 may be registered through video‑conferencing. The judgment clarifies that the procedural requirement of physical presence can be satisfied by a live video link, provided the statutory conditions of notice, free consent and age are fulfilled. The order also directs the Registrar of Marriages to issue appropriate guidelines for technology standards, verification of identities and maintenance of records. This ruling expands access to marriage registration for parties residing in distant locations or under lockdown conditions, while preserving the statutory safeguards of the Act.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "Act",
        "name": "Special Marriage Act, 1954"
      },
      {
        "type": "Court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Video Conferencing"
      },
      {
        "type": "Concept",
        "name": "Marriage Registration"
      },
      {
        "type": "Person",
        "name": "Chief Justice of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "Government Body",
        "name": "Registrar of Marriages"
      },
      {
        "type": "Event",
        "name": "COVID‑19 Pandemic"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background and Petition",
        "content": "Petitioners sought relief after the lockdown restricted physical attendance at the registrar’s office. They argued that the statutory mandate of physical presence violated the right to marry under Article 21 of the Constitution during the health emergency."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Judgment",
        "content": "The Court held that video conferencing can satisfy the requirement of physical presence under the Special Marriage Act, subject to verification of identity, free consent, and age. It emphasized that the technology must be secure, real‑time, and recorded."
      },
      {
        "title": "Guidelines for Implementation",
        "content": "The Court directed the Central Government and the Registrar of Marriages to issue detailed procedural guidelines, including: (a) minimum technical specifications for video link; (b) authentication of parties through government‑issued IDs; (c) presence of at least two witnesses via video; and (d) preservation of the video record for a stipulated period."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact and Scope",
        "content": "The order expands accessibility of marriage registration, especially for inter‑state or inter‑regional couples, and sets a precedent for using technology in other statutory registration processes."
      }
    ],
