  {
    "id": "85e1f691-4d94-47a2-8eaa-3dc6414c4d74",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/custody-under-section-167-of-crpc-includes-custody-of-other-investigating-agencies-such-as-ed-not-just-police-supreme-court-234626",
    "title": "Supreme Court Clarifies Custody Under Section 167 CrPC Extends to All Investigating Agencies",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India ruled that \"custody\" under Section 167 of the Code of Criminal Procedure (CrPC) is not limited to police detention but also covers detention by any investigating agency, including the Enforcement Directorate (ED) and other central agencies. The judgment arose from a writ petition challenging the interpretation of custody in cases where non‑police agencies sought to remand a suspect. The Court held that the statutory language of Section 167 is agency‑neutral and that the same procedural safeguards applicable to police custody must apply to other agencies. Consequently, any extension of custody by these agencies must comply with the procedural requirements of Section 167, including judicial oversight and time limits. The ruling has significant implications for the conduct of investigations and the protection of individual liberty across multiple enforcement bodies.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "statute",
        "name": "Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "agency",
        "name": "Enforcement Directorate (ED)"
      },
      {
        "type": "agency",
        "name": "Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Police custody"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Judicial custody"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Section 167 CrPC"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Section 167 of the CrPC – Custody Provision",
        "content": "Section 167 authorises the filing of a charge sheet and provides for the remand of an accused person in police or judicial custody while investigations are ongoing, subject to a maximum period of 60 or 90 days depending on the nature of the offence."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Decision",
        "content": "The Court clarified that the term \"custody\" is not confined to police detention; it includes any form of physical detention by any investigating agency, and the procedural safeguards of Section 167 apply uniformly."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications for Investigating Agencies",
        "content": "All central and state investigating agencies must now seek judicial approval before extending custody, adhere to the prescribed time limits, and ensure that the rights of the detained person are protected in the same manner as under police custody."
      }
    ],
