  {
    "id": "6d01bd2d-3c5e-4d1e-9d85-111579aeb6b4",
    "source": "https://www.barandbench.com/news/litigation/marriage-not-merely-for-carnal-pleasure-its-main-purpose-is-to-progenate-madras-high-court",
    "title": "Madras High Court: Marriage is Primarily for Procreation, Not Mere Carnal Pleasure",
    "summary": "The Madras High Court observed that the essential purpose of marriage is procreation and the continuance of family lineage, rather than purely sexual gratification. In interpreting the Hindu Marriage Act, the court emphasized that the intention to have children is a substantive element of a valid marital contract. The judgment clarified that a marriage entered into solely for pleasure, without the intention of procreation, may be vulnerable to challenges under sections dealing with void or voidable marriages. This reasoning impacts divorce proceedings and the assessment of matrimonial disputes where the parties dispute the purpose of their union.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Madras High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "statute",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "legal_concept",
        "name": "Purpose of marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "legal_concept",
        "name": "Procreation"
      },
      {
        "type": "legal_concept",
        "name": "Carnal pleasure"
      },
      {
        "type": "publication",
        "name": "Bar & Bench"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Purpose of Marriage under Indian Law",
        "content": "The court reiterated that the legal definition of marriage incorporates the intent to create offspring, drawing on the legislative intent behind the Hindu Marriage Act and related case law."
      },
      {
        "title": "Court’s Observations on Carnal Pleasure",
        "content": "While acknowledging sexual relations as a facet of marital life, the bench held that pleasure alone does not satisfy the statutory criteria for a valid marriage."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications for Void or Voidable Marriages",
        "content": "A marriage lacking the element of procreation may be susceptible to being declared void under Section 5 of the Hindu Marriage Act, affecting claims of maintenance, alimony, and divorce."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact on Divorce and Custody Proceedings",
        "content": "The judgment provides guidance to lower courts in evaluating the underlying intent of spouses when adjudicating divorce petitions and related custody matters."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
