  {
    "id": "6613b6c4-eb44-4194-a2c7-40a4b13fcdde",
    "source": "https://www.barandbench.com/news/litigation/maintenance-date-of-filing-of-application-madras-high-court",
    "title": "Madras High Court Clarifies Date of Filing for Maintenance Applications",
    "summary": "The Madras High Court, adjudicating a petition under Section 125 of the Criminal Procedure Code, held that the date of filing of a maintenance application is the date on which the petition is duly entered in the court's register, not the date of service of notice to the opposite party. The judgment elucidated that the filing date determines the commencement of the limitation period for filing a revision or appeal. It further observed that any delay in entering the petition in the register cannot be used to extend statutory time limits. The decision provides clear guidance to litigants and courts on procedural timelines in maintenance proceedings, ensuring uniformity in future applications.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Madras High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "statute",
        "name": "Section 125, Criminal Procedure Code (CrPC)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Maintenance"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Limitation period"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Revision"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Appeal"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Date of Filing Defined",
        "content": "The Court defined the date of filing as the date on which the petition is entered into the court's register after verification of the necessary documents, regardless of any subsequent administrative delays."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact on Limitation Period",
        "content": "The filing date triggers the limitation period for filing a revision or appeal. The Court emphasized that parties cannot claim an extended period based on the date of service of notice."
      },
      {
        "title": "Procedural Requirements",
        "content": "The judgment reiterated the need for complete documentation and proper verification before entry into the register, as any deficiency may lead to rejection, but does not alter the filing date once entry is made."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legal Reasoning",
        "content": "Relying on precedents and the language of Section 125 CrPC, the Court held that the purpose of the provision is to provide prompt relief to claimants, and thus the date of entry should be determinative."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Madras High Court",
      "maintenance application",
      "date of filing",
      "Section 125 CrPC",
      "limitation period",
      "revision",
      "appeal",
      "court register",
      "procedural law",
      "family law"
    ]
