  {
    "id": "a685ac57-af25-426f-bab5-707097d22a49",
    "source": "https://www.scobserver.in/cases/ashwini-kumar-upadhyay-union-of-india-uniform-adoption-and-guardianship-case-background/",
    "title": "Ashwini Kumar Upadhyay v. Union of India – Uniform Adoption and Guardianship Case Background",
    "summary": "The case of Ashwini Kumar Upadhyay v. Union of India concerns the long‑standing demand for a Uniform Adoption and Guardianship Act to replace the fragmented personal‑law based adoption statutes in India. The petitioner argued that the existing framework, comprising the Hindu Adoption and Maintenance Act, the Guardians and Wards Act, and the Juvenile Justice (Care and Protection of Children) Act, created disparities and impeded the best interests of children. The Supreme Court examined the constitutional validity of the proposed uniform legislation, its alignment with the right to equality, and the duty of the State to protect children. While the Court upheld the need for a uniform law, it directed the legislature to expedite the enactment of the Uniform Adoption and Guardianship Bill, emphasizing procedural safeguards and the paramountcy of child welfare. The judgment has prompted legislative and policy reforms, influencing adoption processes, inter‑religious adoption, and the recognition of guardianship across personal law communities.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Ashwini Kumar Upadhyay"
      },
      {
        "type": "state",
        "name": "Union of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Uniform Adoption and Guardianship Bill"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Adoption and Maintenance Act, 1956"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Guardians and Wards Act, 1890"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Juvenile Justice (Care and Protection of Children) Act, 2015"
      },
      {
        "type": "authority",
        "name": "Central Adoption Resource Authority (CARA)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Right to equality (Article 14, Constitution of India)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Child's best interests"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background",
        "content": "India's adoption law was fragmented across personal‑law statutes, leading to inconsistencies in adoption procedures for different religious communities. The petitioner highlighted the need for a single, secular law that would ensure uniformity, protect children's rights, and simplify the adoption process."
      },
      {
        "title": "Issues Raised",
        "content": "Key issues included: (1) violation of Article 14 due to differential treatment; (2) lack of statutory provisions for inter‑religious adoption; (3) the inadequacy of guardianship provisions under the existing Acts; and (4) the necessity to align adoption law with international conventions such as the Hague Convention on Inter‑Country Adoption."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Findings",
        "content": "The Court recognized the legitimacy of the petitioner's concerns, affirmed that the State has a constitutional duty to protect children, and upheld the principle that a uniform law would advance the child's right to equality. It declined to strike down existing statutes but directed Parliament to enact the Uniform Adoption and Guardianship Bill without undue delay."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact and Legislative Response",
        "content": "Following the judgment, the Ministry of Women and Child Development accelerated drafting of the Uniform Adoption and Guardianship Bill. The proposed law seeks to replace the Hindu Adoption and Maintenance Act, the Guardians and Wards Act, and the relevant provisions of the Juvenile Justice Act, introducing a single procedure for adoption and guardianship irrespective of religion."
      },
      {
        "title": "Current Status",
        "content": "As of the latest updates, the Bill is pending parliamentary approval. Interim measures include procedural guidelines issued by CARA to streamline inter‑religious adoptions and safeguard the child's welfare pending the enactment of the uniform law."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Uniform Adoption and Guardianship",
      "Supreme Court of India",
      "Ashwini Kumar Upadhyay",
      "Child welfare",
      "Personal law",
      "Hindu Adoption and Maintenance Act",
      "Guardians and Wards Act",
      "Juvenile Justice Act",
      "Equality clause",
      "Inter‑religious adoption",
      "CARA",
      "Constitutional law",
      "Legislative reform",
      "Best interests of the child"
    ]
  },
