  {
    "id": "1e8818e7-ce58-461a-9d51-c50b2996ab79",
    "source": "http://indiankanoon.org:80/doc/1000000/",
    "title": "Major General A.K. Kapur v. Union of India (Delhi High Court, 19 Feb 2009)",
    "summary": "The petitioner, Major General A.K. Kapur, sought direction for his promotion to Lieutenant General after a Special Selection Board recommended him, but the Appointments Committee of the Cabinet withheld approval citing a vigilance‑related ban (DV Ban). The hold was based on a CBI FIR alleging possession of disproportionate assets, which the petitioner contested as unfounded. The Delhi High Court examined whether the ACC could lawfully withhold promotion on such grounds and emphasized that false or motivated allegations must not prejudice an officer’s unblemished record. Ultimately, the Court underscored the need for a balanced approach between accountability and protection of meritorious officers in matters of defence‑service promotions.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Major General A.K. Kapur"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Delhi High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "judge",
        "name": "Justice Sanjay Kishan Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "judge",
        "name": "Justice Mool Chand Garg"
      },
      {
        "type": "government",
        "name": "Union of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "agency",
        "name": "Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI)"
      },
      {
        "type": "body",
        "name": "Appointments Committee of the Cabinet (ACC)"
      },
      {
        "type": "body",
        "name": "Special Selection Board (SSB)"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background",
        "content": "Petitioner joined the Army in 1971, rose to Major General, and was considered for promotion to Lieutenant General by a Special Selection Board on 5 Nov 2007."
      },
      {
        "title": "CBI FIR and DV Ban",
        "content": "A CBI FIR dated 8 Oct 2007 alleged that the petitioner possessed assets disproportionate to his known sources of income. The ACC placed the promotion case in abeyance, treating it as a vigilance‑related ban (DV Ban)."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legal Issues",
        "content": "Whether the ACC could lawfully withhold promotion on the basis of an unproven FIR and whether the petitioner’s right to promotion could be overridden by mere suspicion."
      },
      {
        "title": "Court Findings",
        "content": "The Court acknowledged the ACC’s discretion but warned that false or motivated allegations should not tarnish a clean service record. It highlighted the need for a balanced preliminary inquiry before registering an FIR against senior officers."
      },
      {
        "title": "Conclusion",
        "content": "The judgment emphasizes protecting merit‑based promotions in the armed forces while ensuring vigilance, and calls for procedural fairness before imposing a DV Ban."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "promotion",
      "army",
      "Special Selection Board",
      "Appointments Committee of the Cabinet",
      "Central Bureau of Investigation",
      "FIR",
