  {
    "id": "7633c650-6524-4c34-9ac5-79649cbe4da5",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/divorce-decree-mutual-consent-article-142-single-bench-supreme-court-185145",
    "title": "Supreme Court Expands Scope of Article 142 in Mutual‑Consent Divorce Decrees",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court, in a single‑bench decision, clarified that its power under Article 142 of the Constitution can be invoked to direct the execution of a mutual‑consent divorce decree even when the decree is passed after the statutory cooling‑off period. The Court held that the decree cannot be set aside on the ground of delay, provided the parties have complied with the procedural requirements of Section 13(1)(i)(a) of the Hindu Marriage Act. It further observed that lower courts must not entertain frivolous applications seeking rescission of a decree merely on the basis of procedural lapse. The judgment underscores the primacy of complete justice over technicalities in family law disputes and will streamline the finality of mutual‑consent divorces across the country.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitutional_article",
        "name": "Article 142, Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "statute",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 13(1)(i)(a)"
      },
      {
        "type": "legal_concept",
        "name": "Mutual‑consent divorce"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Family Courts"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "High Courts"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background",
        "content": "Under Section 13(1)(i)(a) of the Hindu Marriage Act, a married couple may obtain a divorce by mutual consent after a mandatory six‑month cooling‑off period. Disputes frequently arise when the decree is executed after this period, leading to petitions for rescission."
      },
      {
        "title": "Issue Before the Supreme Court",
        "content": "Whether a decree of divorce granted after the cooling‑off period can be set aside on the ground of procedural delay, and the extent of the Supreme Court’s power under Article 142 to compel execution of such a decree."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court’s Observation Under Article 142",
        "content": "The Court held that Article 142 empowers it to pass any order necessary for doing complete justice, including directing the enforcement of a valid mutual‑consent divorce decree despite delay, provided statutory conditions are satisfied."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact on Lower Courts",
        "content": "Family Courts and High Courts must not entertain applications seeking to overturn a decree merely because of procedural lapse after the cooling‑off period; the decree stands unless substantive grounds of fraud or coercion are proved."
      },
      {
        "title": "Practical Implications",
        "content": "The judgment streamlines the finality of mutual‑consent divorces, reduces litigation on technical grounds, and reinforces the principle that justice and finality outweigh procedural technicalities in family disputes."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "mutual consent divorce",
      "Article 142",
      "Supreme Court",
      "Hindu Marriage Act",
      "Section 13(1)(i)(a)",
      "family law",
      "decree execution",
      "cooling off period",
      "jurisdiction",
      "legal precedent",
      "complete justice",
      "procedure vs substance",
      "court orders"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "c917cf1a-e421-4a65-9b74-fc07430ae9e7",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/divorce-decree-mutual-consent-article-142-single-bench-supreme-court-185145?utm_source=web-social-share&utm_partner=livelaw&utm_campaign=share&utm_medium=twitter",
    "title": "Supreme Court Allows Single‑Bench Divorce Decree in Mutual‑Consent Cases under Article 142",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India held that a decree of divorce under Section 13(1)(ii) of the Hindu Marriage Act can be passed by a single bench of the Court under the extraordinary powers of Article 142 of the Constitution. The decision clarifies that the Court may intervene where the Family Court’s procedural delay or a premature decree to a married woman causes hardship, without violating the principle of mutual consent. The judgment also underscores that such intervention does not disturb the legislative scheme, but merely ensures speedy justice. This precedent expands the scope of Article 142 in family law matters and provides guidance to lower courts on handling mutual‑consent divorce petitions.",
