        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 13(1)(ii)"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitution_article",
        "name": "Article 142 of the Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Mutual‑consent divorce"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice [Name not disclosed]"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background of the Petition",
        "content": "A married woman obtained a divorce decree from the Family Court before her husband could file a mutual‑consent petition, prompting her husband to approach the Supreme Court for relief."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legal Issue",
        "content": "Whether a single bench of the Supreme Court can exercise its extraordinary jurisdiction under Article 142 to pass a decree of divorce under Section 13(1)(ii)."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Holding",
        "content": "The Court affirmed that it may, in exceptional circumstances, pass a divorce decree via a single bench under Article 142, provided the decision aligns with the statutory scheme and serves the interest of justice."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications for Family Law Practice",
        "content": "Lower courts must ensure procedural efficiency in mutual‑consent cases to avoid unnecessary Supreme Court intervention; parties can now seek relief directly from the apex Court where delay causes prejudice."
      },
      {
        "title": "Conclusion",
        "content": "The judgment broadens the application of Article 142, reinforcing the Supreme Court’s role in delivering swift justice in family disputes without contravening the legislative intent of the Hindu Marriage Act."
      }
    ],
