    "summary": "The Supreme Court, in a single‑bench decision, held that it can pass a divorce decree in mutual‑consent cases even when the period of separation prescribed under Section 13(b) of the Hindu Marriage Act has not elapsed, invoking its extraordinary jurisdiction under Article 142 of the Constitution. The Court emphasized that Article 142 empowers it to do \"complete justice\" and to fill legislative gaps, allowing it to order a decree when parties have a bona‑fide settlement and the petition is not opposed. While the statutory six‑month cooling‑off period remains, the Court clarified that an equitable relief can be granted in exceptional circumstances. The ruling is expected to streamline divorce proceedings and set a precedent for future applications of Article 142 in family law matters.",
