  {
    "id": "c540eb85-5d4b-4b0c-ba1d-0b208e7cbbe8",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/divorced-muslim-woman-can-seek-maintenance-from-husband-under-s125-crpc-supreme-court-262843",
    "title": "Supreme Court allows divorced Muslim women to claim maintenance under Section 125 CrPC",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India ruled that a divorced Muslim woman is entitled to claim maintenance from her former husband under Section 125 of the Criminal Procedure Code, despite the existence of separate personal law provisions. The judgment clarifies that the statutory right to maintenance is a secular remedy that cannot be denied on the ground of religion. The Court emphasized that the purpose of Section 125 is to prevent destitution and vagrancy, and it applies uniformly to all citizens irrespective of personal law. This decision bridges the gap between Muslim personal law and the general criminal law framework, ensuring gender‑neutral protection for divorced women. The ruling is expected to influence future cases involving maintenance under personal law disputes.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "statute",
        "name": "Section 125, Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Maintenance (Alimony)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Muslim Personal Law"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Divorced Muslim woman (beneficiary)"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Husband (obligor)"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background",
        "content": "Historically, divorced Muslim women could only claim maintenance under the provisions of Muslim personal law, which were often restrictive and varied across schools of thought. Many petitions alleged that this framework left them without adequate financial support."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Verdict",
        "content": "In a landmark ruling, the Court held that Section 125 CrPC provides a universal right to maintenance and is applicable to Muslim women as well. The decision dismissed the contention that personal law could bar the application of the secular statute."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legal Reasoning",
        "content": "The Court observed that Section 125 was enacted to prevent vagrancy and destitution, objectives that transcend religious considerations. It reiterated that any law that curtails this constitutional guarantee would be unconstitutional."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications",
        "content": "The judgment ensures that divorced Muslim women can approach civil courts for maintenance, aligning their rights with those of women from other religions. It also sets a precedent for harmonising personal law with secular statutes in matters of social welfare."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "maintenance",
      "alimony",
      "divorce",
      "Muslim women",
      "Section 125 CrPC",
      "Supreme Court",
      "personal law",
      "gender equality",
      "civil remedy",
      "Criminal Procedure Code",
      "destitution",
      "legal precedent",
      "Indian family law",
      "secular legislation"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "3d6f9e40-c632-4829-96aa-9241e69d724b",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/divorced-muslim-woman-can-seek-maintenance-from-husband-under-s125-crpc-supreme-court-262843?fbclid=IwZXh0bgNhZW0CMTEAAR2g2dylzs55kOtSmmdKaxOdETtyLkjj0KVNtcvxwUqYqCdREOjogbq30bI_aem_xpB17rbvagaQGc7ridxAsg",
    "title": "Supreme Court Allows Divorced Muslim Women to Claim Maintenance Under Section 125 CrPC",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court held that a divorced Muslim woman is entitled to claim maintenance under Section 125 of the Criminal Procedure Code, irrespective of the provisions of the Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986. The judgment clarifies that the Act does not oust the jurisdiction of Section 125 CrPC, which provides a uniform remedy for alimony across all personal laws. The Court emphasized the constitutional guarantee of gender equality and the right to a dignified life for women. This ruling expands the scope of maintenance relief for Muslim women and aligns personal law with the broader welfare provisions of the CrPC.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
