      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Maintenance / Alimony"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Gender Equality"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Dignity of Women"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background",
        "content": "A petition filed by a divorced Muslim woman challenged the view that the Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986 was the exclusive source of maintenance, seeking relief under Section 125 CrPC."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legal Issue",
        "content": "Whether the provisions of Section 125 CrPC are applicable to divorced Muslim women notwithstanding the existence of the Muslim Women (Protection of Rights on Divorce) Act, 1986."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Holding",
        "content": "The Court held that Section 125 CrPC is a secular provision that cannot be excluded by any personal law. Therefore, a divorced Muslim woman can claim maintenance under this provision."
      },
      {
        "title": "Rationale",
        "content": "The judgment relied on constitutional guarantees of equality (Article 14) and the right to life and dignity (Article 21), interpreting the 1986 Act as complementary, not restrictive, to Section 125."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications",
        "content": "The decision standardises maintenance relief across communities, ensures better financial security for divorced Muslim women, and reinforces the primacy of welfare legislation over personal law where they intersect."
      }
    ],
