  {
    "id": "941af91a-1e1f-495a-aaa1-b2910a8f39d4",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-between-muslim-man-and-a-hindu-woman-142316",
    "title": "Supreme Court Rules Child of Muslim Man and Hindu Wife Entitled to Father's Property",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court held that a child born out of a marriage between a Muslim man and his Hindu wife is a legitimate heir and may claim a share in the father's property. The Court classified such a marriage as \"fasid\" – irregular but not void – distinguishing it from \"sahih\" (valid) and \"batil\" (void) marriages under Muslim law. Accordingly, offspring of a fasid marriage are considered legitimate, whereas only children born outside wedlock or from a batil marriage are illegitimate. The decision upheld a Kerala High Court judgment affirming the child's right to inheritance and clarified the impact of inter‑faith marriages on property succession under Muslim personal law.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Kerala High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "judge",
        "name": "Justice N.V. Ramana"
      },
      {
        "type": "judge",
        "name": "Justice Mohan M. Shantanagoudar"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Guru Krishnakumar (Senior Advocate)"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Mohammed Ilias"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Valliamma"
      },
      {
        "type": "book",
        "name": "Mulla's Principles of Mahommedan Law"
      },
      {
        "type": "book",
        "name": "Syed Ameer Ali's Principles of Mahommedan Law"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "fasid marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "sahih marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "batil marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "legitimate child"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "inheritance rights"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Classification of Marriages under Muslim Law",
        "content": "The Court reiterated the three categories recognized in Muslim personal law: sahih (valid), batil (void), and fasid (irregular). A fasid marriage is unlawful but not void, meaning it creates civil rights and obligations between the parties."
      },
      {
        "title": "Status of Children Born from Fasid Marriages",
        "content": "Children born of a fasid marriage are deemed legitimate and enjoy the same rights of inheritance as children from a sahih marriage. Only children born outside any marriage or from a batil marriage are considered illegitimate."
      },
      {
        "title": "Property Rights of Legitimate Children",
        "content": "The legitimate child of a Muslim father, irrespective of the mother’s religion, is entitled to a share in the father's immovable property under the applicable personal law and succession rules."
      },
      {
        "title": "Impact on Inter‑faith Marriages",
        "content": "While a marriage between a Muslim man and a Hindu (idol‑worshipper) is not sahih, it is not batil either; it is classified as fasid. Hence, the marriage does not become void, and the offspring retain inheritance rights."
      }
    ],
