  {
    "id": "024a56bb-66bb-4707-854d-2e7650976001",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-between-muslim-man-and-a-hindu-woman-142316?fbclid=IwAR2w6E_gfrSueiC9-r3vFabu1rTVELXBUyQlP-JUWlCnoQDPJpOQCqiEbLk",
    "title": "Child born of marriage between Muslim man and Hindu woman entitled to claim father's property: Supreme Court",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India held that a child born of a marriage between a Muslim man and his Hindu wife is entitled to a share in the father's property. The Court characterized such a marriage as an irregular (fasid) marriage, distinct from a valid (sahih) or void (batil) marriage under Muslim personal law. Consequently, the offspring of a fasid marriage are legitimate, and only children born out of a void marriage or outside wedlock are considered illegitimate. The judgment relied on classical Muslim law texts, including Mulla's and Syed Ameer Ali's principles, and affirmed the decision of the Kerala High Court.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Kerala High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "judge",
        "name": "Justice N.V. Ramana"
      },
