        "name": "Justice Mohan M. Shantanagoudar"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Mohammed Ilias"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Valliamma"
      },
      {
        "type": "advocate",
        "name": "Guru Krishnakumar"
      },
      {
        "type": "act_concept",
        "name": "Muslim Personal Law"
      },
      {
        "type": "act_concept",
        "name": "Mulla's Principles of Mahommedan Law"
      },
      {
        "type": "act_concept",
        "name": "Syed Ameer Ali's Principles of Mahommedan Law"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Nature of Marriage under Muslim Law",
        "content": "The Court explained the tripartite classification of marriages in Muslim law: sahih (valid), batil (void), and fasid (irregular). A marriage between a Muslim man and a Hindu (idol-worshipper or fire-worshipper) is not sahih nor batil but falls under fasid, meaning it is unlawful but not void."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legitimacy of Offspring",
        "content": "Children born from a fasid marriage are considered legitimate under Muslim law. Only children of a batil marriage or those born outside of any wedlock are deemed illegitimate and thus barred from inheritance rights."
      },
      {
        "title": "Inheritance Rights of Children from Fasid Marriages",
        "content": "Since the child is legitimate, he/she is entitled to a share in the father's property as per the applicable succession provisions. The Court affirmed that the child of Mohammed Ilias and Valliamma can claim his rightful inheritance."
      },
      {
        "title": "Judicial Reasoning and Precedents",
        "content": "The judgment relied on classical texts, notably Mulla's and Syed Ameer Ali's commentaries, to distinguish between the categories of marriage. It upheld the Kerala High Court's finding and rejected the argument that a Hindu wife has no right to her husband's property in such a marriage."
      }
    ],
