  {
    "id": "5b8756fe-967a-42f3-8ba5-ee47bf16336e",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-between-muslim-man-and-a-hindu-woman-142316?utm_source=mobile-social-share&utm_partner=livelaw&utm_campaign=share&utm_medium=twitter",
    "title": "Supreme Court Declares Child of Muslim Man and Hindu Wife Entitled to Father’s Property",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India held that a child born out of a marriage between a Muslim man and his Hindu wife is a legitimate heir and may claim a share in the father’s property. The Court distinguished between a valid (sahih), void (batil) and irregular (fasid) Muslim marriage, observing that an inter‑faith marriage with a Hindu (idol‑worshipper) is irregular (fasid) rather than void. Consequently, the offspring of a fasid marriage are legitimate, whereas only children of a void (batil) marriage or born out of wedlock are illegitimate. The judgment upheld a Kerala High Court decision confirming the child’s right to inheritance, relying on classical Muslim law texts such as Mulla’s and Syed Ameer Ali’s Principles of Mahomedan Law.",
