    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Classification of Muslim Marriages",
        "content": "The Court reiterated the doctrinal categories under Muslim personal law: sahih (valid), batil (void), and fasid (irregular). A marriage between a Muslim man and a Hindu (idol‑worshipper) is not sahih and not batil; it falls within the fasid category, meaning it is unlawful but not void."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legitimacy and Inheritance Rights of Children from Fasid Marriages",
        "content": "Children born of a fasid marriage are considered legitimate under Muslim law. Hence, they acquire the same inheritance rights as children of a sahih marriage, and only children of a batil marriage or those born out of wedlock are denied succession."
      },
      {
        "title": "Judicial Reasoning and Precedent",
        "content": "Relying on classical authorities such as Mulla’s and Syed Ameer Ali’s texts, the Supreme Court upheld the Kerala High Court’s finding that the plaintiff, the son of Mohammed Ilias and Valliamma, is entitled to his father's share of property. The judgment emphasizes that the irregular nature of the marriage does not extinguish the child's right to inheritance."
      }
    ],
