    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Classification of Muslim Marriages",
        "content": "The Court reiterated the distinction under Muslim personal law between valid (sahih), void (batil), and irregular/invalid (fasid) marriages, emphasizing that a fasid marriage is unlawful but not void and therefore creates rights and obligations."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legitimacy of Children from Fasid Marriages",
        "content": "A child born of a fasid marriage is considered legitimate for purposes of inheritance. Only children born outside any marriage or from a batil marriage are deemed illegitimate."
      },
      {
        "title": "Supreme Court Holding on Property Rights",
        "content": "The Supreme Court upheld the Kerala High Court's finding that the plaintiff, the son of Mohammed Ilias and Valliamma, is entitled to a share in his father's property as a legitimate heir."
      },
      {
        "title": "Implications for Inter‑religious Marriages",
        "content": "The judgment clarifies that a marriage between a Muslim man and a Hindu (idol worshipper) is classified as fasid, not void, thereby protecting the rights of children born from such unions."
      }
