  {
    "id": "3609d867-20cf-47d2-9272-9dfffd751eff",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-considered-pious-in-indian-society-divorce-on-ground-of-irretrievable-breakdown-of-marriage-not-always-desirable-supreme-court-239856",
    "title": "Supreme Court: Exercise of Article 142 for Divorce on Irretrievable Breakdown Not a Straw‑Hat Formula",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court held that it may invoke its inherent power under Article 142 of the Constitution to dissolve a marriage on the ground of ‘irretrievable breakdown’ even when one spouse opposes the relief, but such discretion must be exercised with great care and caution. The Court emphasized that marriage is a pious and spiritual institution in Indian society and warned against adopting a rigid formula for granting divorce under Article 142. Referring to the recent Constitution Bench judgment in Shilpa Shailesh v. Varun Sreenivasan, the Court reiterated that any exercise of this power must be guided by the principle of ‘complete justice’. In the specific case of an 89‑year‑old husband seeking divorce from his 82‑year‑old wife, the Court declined to grant relief, respecting the wife's sentiment of not wanting the stigma of being a divorcee.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "justice",
        "name": "Justice Aniruddha Bose"
      },
      {
        "type": "justice",
        "name": "Justice Bela M. Trivedi"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitutional_article",
        "name": "Article 142, Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "case",
        "name": "Shilpa Shailesh v. Varun Sreenivasan (2023) LiveLaw (SC) 375"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Irretrievable breakdown of marriage"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Complete justice"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Inherent Power under Article 142",
        "content": "The Court clarified that Article 142 confers inherent powers to the Supreme Court to provide any relief necessary to achieve complete justice, including dissolving a marriage on the ground of irretrievable breakdown, even if one party objects."
      },
      {
        "title": "Judicial Caution and Care",
        "content": "Any exercise of Article 142 must be undertaken with ‘great care and caution’, balancing the equities of the parties and not reducing the discretion to a mechanical formula."
      },
      {
        "title": "Marriage as a Pious Institution",
        "content": "The judgment reiterated the societal view of marriage as a sacred, spiritual union, emphasizing that social norms and emotional bonds should inform the Court’s approach to divorce."
      },
      {
        "title": "Application in the 89‑Year‑Old Husband Case",
        "content": "Despite the husband’s petition for divorce on the ground of irretrievable breakdown, the Court denied relief because the wife, aged 82, wished to remain married and feared the stigma of being a divorcee."
      },
      {
        "title": "Reference to Shilpa Shailesh v. Varun Sreenivasan",
        "content": "The Court relied on the earlier Constitution Bench decision, which affirmed that Article 142 can be used to dissolve a marriage for complete justice, but reiterated that such power is not a substitute for statutory grounds under the Hindu Marriage Act."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Article 142",
      "irretrievable breakdown",
      "divorce",
      "Supreme Court",
      "Hindu Marriage Act 1955",
      "inherent powers",
      "complete justice",
      "marital piety",
      "social norms",
      "gender stigma",
      "judicial discretion",
      "constitutional law",
      "family law"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "11c7fb6a-7a0d-4791-9eb2-aef837bdd21c",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-contracted-during-pendency-of-mat-appeal-152996",
    "title": "Supreme Court Holds Marriage During Pendency of Belated Divorce Appeal Is Not Void",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court ruled that a marriage entered into while an appeal against a divorce decree is pending is not void ab initio when the appeal is filed after the limitation period has expired. Referring to Sections 5, 11 and 15 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955, the Court observed that legislative intent does not deem a subsequent marriage void merely because a belated appeal is later filed. Section 15 bars remarriage only when an appeal is filed within the prescribed period or when the decree is stayed, neither of which applied here. Consequently, the Court allowed the maintenance petition and directed the husband to pay maintenance to the wife.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act, 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Indira Banerjee"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice M.R. Shah"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 5 of the Hindu Marriage Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 11 of the Hindu Marriage Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "section",
        "name": "Section 15 of the Hindu Marriage Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "limitation period for filing appeal"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "maintenance under the Hindu Marriage Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "void marriage"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Legal Issue",
        "content": "Whether a second marriage contracted during the pendency of an appeal against a divorce decree, filed after the limitation period for appeal, is void under the Hindu Marriage Act."
      },
      {
        "title": "Court’s Observation on Legislative Intent",
        "content": "The Court held that it could not have been Parliament's intent to render a subsequently contracted marriage void merely because a belated appeal is later filed, especially when the appeal is beyond the limitation period."
      },
      {
        "title": "Application of Section 15",
        "content": "Section 15 bars remarriage only when an appeal is filed within the prescribed limitation period, the decree is stayed, or the appeal is dismissed. In the present case, the appeal was filed almost a year after the limitation period, and no stay order existed, so Section 15 was not attracted."
      },
      {
        "title": "Holding and Relief",
        "content": "The Supreme Court allowed the maintenance petition, directing the husband to pay maintenance to the wife, and affirmed that the second marriage is valid and not void."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "marriage",
      "divorce decree",
      "appeal",
      "limitation period",
      "Hindu Marriage Act",
      "Section 15",
      "void marriage",
      "maintenance",
