      "stay order",
      "remarriage",
      "legal intent",
      "case law"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "5398e836-41b6-4148-b864-7a9a754cf241",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-5-reasons-why-supreme-court-didnt-include-same-sex-unions-under-special-marriage-act-240413",
    "title": "Supreme Court Declines to Read Down Special Marriage Act for Same‑Sex Unions",
    "summary": "On 17 October 2023 the Supreme Court Constitution Bench unanimously held that it could not strike down or read down the Special Marriage Act, 1954 to include non‑heterosexual unions. The Court reasoned that such a modification would involve complex workability issues, especially under Section 21A, and would constitute a legislative exercise reserved for Parliament. It also warned that voiding the Act for excluding queer couples would revert India to a pre‑independence regime of social inequality. The bench emphasized the institutional limitation of the judiciary in undertaking law‑making and reiterated that any amendment to the Act must be effected by the legislature.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Special Marriage Act, 1954"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice S.K. Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Ravindra Bhat"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice P.S. Narasimha"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Hima Kohli"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Reading down (judicial interpretation)"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Legislative competence"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Article 14 of the Constitution"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Article 15 of the Constitution"
      },
      {
        "type": "institution",
        "name": "Parliament of India"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Judgement Overview",
        "content": "The Constitution Bench, comprising Chief Justice Chandrachud and four other judges, unanimously refused to strike down or read down the Special Marriage Act to accommodate same‑sex marriages, stating that such a change lies within the legislative domain."
      },
      {
        "title": "Complex Workability under Section 21A",
        "content": "The Court highlighted that Section 21A links the Act to personal and non‑personal succession laws, creating a ‘spider’s web’ of legislative inter‑dependencies that would make any amendment highly complex and potentially disruptive."
      },
      {
        "title": "Historical Context and Pre‑Independence Era Concern",
        "content": "Chief Justice Chandrachud warned that declaring the Act void for excluding queer couples would revert India to a pre‑independence scenario where inter‑religious and inter‑caste marriages were barred, undermining the secular purpose of the SMA."
      },
      {
        "title": "Judicial Legislation vs Legislative Domain",
        "content": "The bench stressed that reading gender‑neutral words into the SMA would amount to judicial legislation, which is impermissible. The Court emphasized its institutional limitations and the need for Parliament to undertake any reform."
      },
      {
        "title": "Constitutionality Debate",
        "content": "While Justice Kaul found the SMA unconstitutional for violating Articles 14 and 15, he concurred with the majority that the appropriate remedy lies with legislative amendment rather than a judicial strike‑down."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "Special Marriage Act",
      "same‑sex marriage",
      "reading down",
      "judicial review",
      "legislative competence",
      "Article 14",
      "Article 15",
      "Section 4",
      "Section 21A",
      "Supreme Court",
      "Chief Justice Chandrachud",
      "queer marriage",
      "Parliament",
      "constitutional law",
      "secular marriage framework"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "74635b52-1630-4b48-9853-1681561b6a0d",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-cji-dy-chandrachud-adoption-queer-couple-children-negative-effects-same-sex-marriage-supreme-court-226766",
    "title": "CJI Chandrachud Rejects Adoption Harm Argument in Marriage Equality Case",
    "summary": "While hearing petitions seeking the extension of marriage rights to same‑sex couples, Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud observed that the claim that children raised by queer couples would suffer psychological harm is contradicted by the fact that Indian law already permits single individuals to adopt. Petitioners, led by Senior Advocate Dr. Abhishek Manu Singhvi, contended that marriage confers the right to adopt and urged the Court to read down the Special Marriage Act (SMA) to include same‑sex unions. The Court examined whether the SMA, enacted as a secular, agnostic legislation, can be interpreted to be inclusive of sexual orientation, invoking Articles 14, 19(1)(a) and 21 of the Constitution. The arguments emphasized equality, freedom of expression, and dignity, warning that a failure to recognise same‑sex marriage would create a discriminatory hierarchy inconsistent with constitutional guarantees.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "D.Y. Chandrachud"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Dr. Abhishek Manu Singhvi"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Dr. A.M. Singhvi"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Utkarsh Saxena"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Ananya Kotia"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Special Marriage Act"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitutional_article",
        "name": "Article 14 of the Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitutional_article",
        "name": "Article 19(1)(a) of the Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitutional_article",
        "name": "Article 21 of the Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Marriage Equality"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Adoption Rights"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Adoption Argument",
        "content": "CJI Chandrachud noted that the existing legal framework already allows a single person, regardless of sexual orientation, to adopt, thereby refuting the contention that adoption by a same‑sex couple would be detrimental to a child’s psychological health."
      },
      {
        "title": "Interpretation of the Special Marriage Act",
        "content": "Petitioners argued that the SMA, drafted as a secular statute to accommodate marriages not recognized by religion, should be read down to embrace same‑sex unions, contending that its purpose is agnostic to both faith and sexual orientation."
      },
      {
        "title": "Constitutional Grounds Invoked",
        "content": "The submissions invoked Articles 14 (equality), 19(1)(a) (freedom of expression), and 21 (right to dignity) of the Constitution, asserting that denying marriage to queer couples creates an unconstitutional hierarchy and infringes on their liberty and dignity."
      },
      {
        "title": "CJI’s Observations",
        "content": "Chief Justice Chandrachud emphasised that the law should evolve with societal changes, questioned the premise that children of same‑sex couples would develop a homosexual orientation, and asked whether the SMA can be interpreted as agnostic to sexual orientation without a ‘leap of faith.’"
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "marriage equality",
      "same‑sex marriage",
      "adoption",
