  {
    "id": "a6f8f2e1-362b-4f63-9487-08bad6a6f4a1",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-conclusions-directions-of-supreme-court-judgments-240529",
    "title": "Supreme Court Directions on Queer Rights and Marriage Equality",
    "summary": "In a split verdict delivered by CJI D.Y. Chandrachud and Justices Sanjay Kishan Kaul, S. Ravindra Bhat and P.S. Narasimha, the Supreme Court issued extensive directives to Union, State and UT governments to eliminate discrimination against the queer community in access to services, public perception and medical treatment. The Court mandated the cessation of conversion‑therapy, the establishment of safe‑house networks and hotlines, and the recognition of self‑identified gender without compulsory medical procedures. Specific police guidelines were laid down to prevent harassment of queer individuals and couples, including procedural safeguards before filing FIRs. The Court affirmed its jurisdiction under Article 32 and observed that marriage regulation lies with Parliament and state legislatures under Articles 245‑246, leaving space for future queer marriage legislation.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Chief Justice of India D.Y. Chandrachud"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Sanjay Kishan Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
