  {
    "id": "b4d877a5-de0d-4d14-a5ca-75bcb338d2fe",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-conclusions-directions-of-supreme-court-judgments-240529?infinitescroll=1",
    "title": "Supreme Court Directions on Queer Rights and Marriage Equality",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court, through Chief Justice D.Y. Chandrachud and Justices Sanjay Kishan Kaul, S. Ravindra Bhat and P.S. Narasimha, issued sweeping directives to Union, State and Union Territory governments to eliminate discrimination against LGBTQ+ persons, establish safe houses, cease conversion therapies, and recognize self‑identified gender without coercive medical procedures. The Court mandated the inclusion of queer mental‑health modules under the Mental Healthcare Act and instructed police to refrain from harassment, ensure protection, and conduct preliminary investigations before registering FIRs against queer individuals. It affirmed its jurisdiction under Article 32, described queerness as a natural phenomenon, and clarified that the regulation of marriage, including queer marriage, falls within the legislative competence of Parliament and state legislatures under Articles 245 and 246. These directions aim to operationalise marriage equality and broader LGBTQ+ rights in India.",
