    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Directions to Union, State and UT Governments",
        "content": "Governments must prevent discrimination based on gender identity or sexual orientation, ensure equal access to goods and services, sensitise the public, set up harassment helplines, provide district‑wide safe houses (Garima Grehs), halt all conversion‑therapy practices, prohibit forced surgical interventions on inter‑sex children, and recognise self‑identified gender as male, female or third gender without coercive medical conditions."
      },
      {
        "title": "Mental Healthcare Act Modules",
        "content": "The appropriate government shall formulate modules under Section 29(1) of the Mental Healthcare Act to address the mental health of queer persons, and programmes to reduce suicide under Section 29(2) must incorporate provisions targeting queer identity."
      },
      {
        "title": "Police Machinery Directions",
        "content": "Police shall not harass queer couples, shall not force them to return to natal families, must protect their freedom of movement when complaints arise, provide protection against family‑based violence, and conduct a preliminary investigation per Lalita Kumari before registering an FIR, closing complaints where adults are in consensual relationships."
      },
      {
        "title": "Court Conclusions",
        "content": "The Court affirmed its authority under Article 32 to enforce fundamental rights, declared queerness a natural Indian phenomenon, noted that marriage regulation lies with Parliament and state legislatures under Articles 245‑246, and emphasized the need for legislative action to recognise and regulate queer marriage."
      }
    ],
