  {
    "id": "66e3b980-a853-44c7-ab0b-346347a91c5a",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-declaration-of-right-to-marry-necessary-to-end-stigma-against-lgbtqia-community-mukul-rohatgi-argues-in-supreme-court-226670",
    "title": "Supreme Court Marriage Equality Case: Mukul Rohatgi Argues Declaration of Right to Marry for LGBTQIA+ Community",
    "summary": "Petitions seeking legal recognition for same‑sex marriage were heard before a Constitution bench of the Supreme Court of India. Senior Advocate Mukul Rohatgi, appearing for the petitioners, sought a two‑fold relief: a declaration that marriage is a fundamental right for queer individuals under Articles 14, 19 and 21 of the Constitution, and that this right be recognised through an inclusive reading of the Special Marriage Act. He relied on precedents such as Navtej Singh Johar v. Union of India, Justice K.S. Puttaswamy (Retd) v. Union of India and Anuj Garg & Ors v. Hotel Association of India, and highlighted global developments to argue that state recognition would eliminate societal stigma. Rohatgi countered the Centre’s contention that the petitions represented a narrow, urban elite view, emphasizing that constitutional rights evolve with time and are not dependent on popular will. The arguments framed marriage equality as essential for the assimilation and equal treatment of the LGBTQIA+ community in India.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Chief Justice of India D.Y. Chandrachud"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Sanjay Kishan Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Ravindra Bhat"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
