  {
    "id": "b1a6dd86-7a85-4326-ab8c-a1d175ac03df",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-key-highlights-from-the-landmark-hearing-before-supreme-court-240304",
    "title": "Supreme Court Hearing Highlights on Marriage Equality Petitions",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court of India heard twenty petitions seeking recognition of queer marriages under the Special Marriage Act, Hindu Marriage Act and Foreign Marriage Act. The bench, led by Chief Justice DY Chandrachud, limited the scope to the Special Marriage Act, avoiding personal law matters. The Centre argued that marriage is a legislative matter and that the petitioners represent \"urban elitist\" views, but the Court rejected these contentions. The hearing also featured a debate on gender fluidity, with the Solicitor General asserting a biological definition of gender, which the Chief Justice challenged. A judgment is expected soon, carrying significant implications for LGBTQIA+ rights in India.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Special Marriage Act 1954"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Hindu Marriage Act 1955"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Foreign Marriage Act 1969"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Chief Justice DY Chandrachud"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Sanjay Kishan Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice S Ravindra Bhat"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Hima Kohli"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice PS Narasimha"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Solicitor General Tushar Mehta"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Senior Advocate KV Vishwanathan"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Senior Advocate Jayna Kothari"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Zainab Patel"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Akkai Padmashali"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Marriage Equality"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "LGBTQIA+ Rights"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Gender Fluidity"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Personal Laws"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Maintainability"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "I. Centre Challenges Maintainability of the Petitions",
        "content": "The Union government argued that only the legislature can create or recognise marriage under Article 246 of the Constitution, contending that the Court lacks jurisdiction to grant marriage rights to same‑sex couples. The Chief Justice sought clarification on the petitioners’ canvas before addressing the maintainability issue."
      },
      {
        "title": "II. Court Limits Challenge to Special Marriage Act",
        "content": "The bench announced it would confine its review to the Special Marriage Act, deliberately avoiding any interference with personal laws such as the Hindu Marriage Act. Both the Chief Justice and Justice Kaul advocated an incremental approach, focusing on a narrow statutory issue."
      },
      {
        "title": "III. Centre Labels Petitioners as ‘Urban Elitists’; Court Rejects Claim",
        "content": "In a counter‑affidavit, the Centre described the push for marriage equality as representing only urban elitist opinions and alleged that the popular will favours heterosexual marriage. The Supreme Court rejected this narrative, noting the absence of data and highlighting personal stories of transgender litigants to underscore the broader societal relevance."
      },
      {
        "title": "IV. Debate on Gender Fluidity",
        "content": "Solicitor General Tushar Mehta maintained that the terms ‘man’ and ‘woman’ in the Special Marriage Act should be interpreted strictly on biological grounds. Chief Justice Chandrachud challenged this view, asserting that gender identity transcends mere biology, opening the discourse to a more expansive understanding of gender."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
