    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background of the October 2023 Judgment",
        "content": "On 17 October 2023 the Supreme Court declined to grant legal recognition to queer marriages, stating that such a decision lies with the legislature, while affirming the right of queer couples to cohabit without violence and directing the Union to set up a committee to examine their rights."
      },
      {
        "title": "Composition of the New Review Bench",
        "content": "The newly constituted bench consists of Justices B.R. Gavai, Surya Kant, B.V. Nagarathna, P.S. Narasimha and Dipankar Datta. Justice Sanjiv Khanna recused himself, and the previously serving judges CJI D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice S.K. Kaul and Justice Hima Kohli have retired."
      },
      {
        "title": "Issues Raised in the Review Petitions",
        "content": "Petitioners argue that the October judgment contains 'errors apparent on the face of the record', is self‑contradictory, and fails to prohibit discrimination against queer couples, thereby violating their fundamental rights."
      },
      {
        "title": "Court’s Observations on Queer Rights",
        "content": "While the original bench recognized the need for a committee to study the entitlements of queer unions and affirmed the right to cohabit, it stopped short of ordering legal recognition of such relationships as marriage or civil unions."
      },
      {
        "title": "Hearing Schedule and Procedural Notes",
        "content": "The review petitions will be considered in chambers on 9 January 2025 at 1:55 PM, meaning no open courtroom hearing. The bench will examine the merits of the petitions and determine whether to modify or uphold the October 2023 decision."
      }
    ],
