  {
    "id": "aaebdd56-ff5b-48b6-93a5-b8c483985e61",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-no-right-for-queer-couples-to-adopt-children-supreme-court-holds-by-32-majority-240359",
    "title": "Supreme Court Rejects Marriage Equality and Adoption Rights for Queer Couples (Supriyo v. Union of India)",
    "summary": "The Supreme Court, in a 3:2 majority judgment, declined to grant legal recognition to same‑sex marriages and also denied queer couples the right to adopt jointly. The majority, led by CJI D.Y. Chandrachud and Justice S.K. Kaul, held that CARA Regulation 5(3) violated Article 15 of the Constitution by discriminating against unmarried and queer couples. The dissenting judges upheld the regulation, arguing that the state must ensure stable homes for children and that the regulation was within statutory limits. The case, Supriyo v. Union of India (Writ Petition (Civil) No. 1011 of 2022), therefore leaves the status quo on marriage equality and adoption unchanged.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "C.J.I. D.Y. Chandrachud"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice S.K. Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Ravindra Bhat"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice P.S. Narasimha"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice Hima Kohli"
      },
      {
        "type": "organisation",
        "name": "Central Adoption Resource Authority (CARA)"
      },
      {
        "type": "regulation",
        "name": "CARA Regulation 5(3)"
      },
      {
        "type": "constitutional provision",
        "name": "Article 15, Constitution of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "case",
        "name": "Supriyo v. Union of India"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Marriage Equality Issue",
        "content": "The bench examined petitions seeking recognition of same‑sex marriages under Indian law. By a 3:2 majority, the Court held that the Constitution does not currently provide a right to marriage equality for queer couples, leaving the existing legal framework unchanged."
      },
      {
        "title": "Adoption Rights for Queer Couples",
        "content": "The central question was whether CARA Regulation 5(3), which restricts adoption to couples with at least two years of stable marriage, violates Article 15. The majority found the regulation unconstitutional, allowing unmarried and queer couples to adopt jointly, while the minority upheld the regulation."
      },
      {
        "title": "Majority Opinion (CJI Chandrachud & Justice Kaul)",
        "content": "The majority concluded that CARA had exceeded its authority; the requirement of a two‑year marital relationship lacks a rational nexus with child welfare and constitutes indirect discrimination against atypical unions, violating Article 15."
      },
      {
        "title": "Dissenting Opinion (Justices Bhat, Kohli, Narasimha)",
        "content": "The dissent argued that the state, as parens patriae, must safeguard stable homes for children and that the regulation is a permissible classification aimed at achieving that objective; they held the regulation constitutional."
      },
      {
        "title": "Legal Outcome",
        "content": "The judgment (2023 LiveLaw (SC) 900) results in a split verdict: marriage equality is not recognized, but the majority opinion opens the door for queer and unmarried couples to adopt, subject to future clarification."
      }
    ],
