      "majority judgment",
      "dissenting opinion",
      "family law",
      "queer rights",
      "marriage equality",
      "Indian Constitution",
      "stable home"
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "7945de8a-6a44-4da3-b344-9ab1bc2c4e25",
    "source": "https://www.livelaw.in/top-stories/marriage-equality-case-supreme-court-review-petition-queer-couples-241432",
    "title": "Review Petition Challenging Supreme Court's Refusal to Legalise Same‑Sex Marriage",
    "summary": "A review petition has been filed in the Supreme Court of India by four queer activists (Udit Sood, Saatvic, Lakshmi Manoharan and Gagandeep Paul) contesting the Court’s judgment in Supriyo v. Union of India, which declined to recognise same‑sex marriage. The petition argues that the judgment is self‑contradictory, unjust and constitutes an abdication of the Court’s duty to protect fundamental rights of LGBTQ+ individuals. It raises five specific grounds, chiefly the failure to interpret the Special Marriage Act, 1954 in a gender‑neutral manner and the refusal to acknowledge a constitutional right to a civil union for non‑heterosexual couples. The petitioners contend that the judgment violates Articles 14, 15 and 21 of the Constitution and breaches the principle of separation of powers.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Supreme Court of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "case",
        "name": "Supriyo v. Union of India"
      },
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Special Marriage Act, 1954"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Udit Sood"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Saatvic"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Lakshmi Manoharan"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Gagandeep Paul"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Justice S.K. Kaul"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Fundamental Rights"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Discrimination"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Civil Union"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Separation of Powers"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Ground 1 – Interpretation of the Special Marriage Act, 1954",
        "content": "The petitioners claim the Supreme Court erred by refusing to read the Special Marriage Act in a gender‑neutral manner, thereby excluding same‑sex couples despite the Act’s purported purpose of allowing \"any two persons\" to marry. They rely on Justice S.K. Kaul’s dissent that the Act, if intended solely for inter‑faith marriage, cannot justify exclusion of non‑heterosexual partners and that the provision violates Article 14."
      },
      {
        "title": "Ground 2 – Right to a Civil Union for Non‑Heterosexual Couples",
        "content": "Even if marriage is not extended, the petition argues that the Court should have recognised a fundamental right to a civil union, which could be operationalised by permitting registration of queer relationships under Sections 15 and 16 of the Special Marriage Act, thereby affording legal protection and benefits."
      },
      {
        "title": "Ground 3 – Failure to Enforce Constitutional Equality Guarantees",
        "content": "The petition alleges the judgment ignored the Constitution’s guarantee of equality before the law (Article 14) and the right to life and personal liberty (Article 21), rendering the decision self‑contradictory and manifestly unjust."
      },
      {
        "title": "Ground 4 – Abdication of Judicial Duty and Separation of Powers",
        "content": "The review contends that by acknowledging discrimination yet refusing to intervene, the Court abdicated its constitutional obligation and misapplied the doctrine of separation of powers, effectively leaving the State unchecked in violating fundamental rights."
      },
      {
        "title": "Ground 5 – Errors Apparent on the Face of the Record",
        "content": "The petitioners assert that the majority judgment contains clear factual and legal mistakes that are evident from the case record, warranting a reversal or amendment of the decision."
      }
    ],
    "keywords": [
      "same‑sex marriage",
      "LGBTQ+ rights",
      "Special Marriage Act",
