    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background Judgment (17 Oct 2023)",
        "content": "A five‑judge bench held that recognition of queer marriages is a legislative issue, refusing to grant legal status to same‑sex marriages while acknowledging the right to cohabit without violence and directing the Union to set up a committee to study rights of queer unions."
      },
      {
        "title": "New Bench Composition for Review",
        "content": "Retired Justices Sanjay Kishan Kaul and S. Ravindra Bhat have been replaced by Justices Sanjiv Khanna and B.V. Nagarathna. The bench now consists of CJI D.Y. Chandrachud, Justice Hima Kohli, Justice P.S. Narasimha and the two new judges."
      },
      {
        "title": "Issues Raised in Review Petitions",
        "content": "Petitioners contend that the October judgment violated fundamental rights, contained self‑contradictions, and amounted to judicial abdication. They seek a declaration that the denial of marriage recognition is unconstitutional and request directions for legislative or judicial remedies."
      },
      {
        "title": "Court’s Observations on Queer Rights",
        "content": "While the bench affirmed the right to cohabit and suggested a committee on queer unions, it split on the notion of a civil union, with CJI Chandrachud and Justice SK Kaul in favour, and the other three judges dissenting."
      },
      {
        "title": "Potential Outcomes",
        "content": "The review may result in a reaffirmation of the status quo, a directive for Parliament to enact marriage‑equality legislation, or a judicially enforceable civil‑union framework, thereby influencing the trajectory of LGBTQ rights in Indian family law."
      }
    ],
