  {
    "id": "0b575a4a-d724-4031-9841-fec9b00f7edb",
    "source": "https://taxguru.in/corporate-law/conversion-law-bar-interfaith-marriage-live-in-relationships-allahabad-hc.html",
    "title": "Allahabad HC Declares UP Conversion Act Does Not Bar Interfaith Marriages or Live‑In Relationships",
    "summary": "The Allahabad High Court, in Noori & Another v. State of UP (Writ‑C No. 41127 of 2025), held that the Uttar Pradesh Prohibition of Unlawful Conversion of Religion Act, 2021 does not prohibit inter‑faith marriages nor prevent couples from cohabiting in live‑in relationships. The bench, headed by Justice Vivek Kumar Singh, clarified that an offence under Sections 3 and 5 of the Act requires a conversion achieved through misrepresentation, force, undue influence, coercion, allurement, fraud, or marriage, which is absent in consensual inter‑faith unions. The court granted mandamus directing police protection for the petitioners, emphasizing that the right to choose a partner, irrespective of religion, is protected under Article 21 of the Constitution. The judgment underscores the distinction between genuine conversion and personal choice in relationships, reinforcing individual liberty and personal autonomy.",
    "law_type": "family_law",
    "entities": [
      {
        "type": "act",
        "name": "Uttar Pradesh Prohibition of Unlawful Conversion of Religion Act, 2021"
      },
      {
        "type": "court",
        "name": "Allahabad High Court"
      },
      {
        "type": "case",
        "name": "Noori & Another v. State of UP and 4 Others"
      },
      {
        "type": "judge",
        "name": "Justice Vivek Kumar Singh"
      },
      {
        "type": "person",
        "name": "Shwetashwa Agarwal"
      },
      {
        "type": "concept",
        "name": "Article 21 of the Constitution of India"
      }
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Background of the Petitions",
        "content": "Twelve writ petitions were filed by inter‑faith couples—seven Muslim women with Hindu men and five Hindu women with Muslim men—seeking police protection against threats from family members and others."
      },
      {
        "title": "Interpretation of \"Conversion\" under the Act",
        "content": "The Court examined Sections 3 and 5 of the Act and the definition of \"conversion\" in Section 2(c), concluding that a conversion must involve renouncing one’s religion and adopting another through coercive or fraudulent means, which does not apply to consensual inter‑faith relationships."
      },
      {
        "title": "Holding on Interfaith Marriage and Live‑In Relationships",
        "content": "The judgment unequivocally states that the Act neither forbids inter‑faith marriages nor live‑in relationships, and such unions are protected by the fundamental right to life and personal liberty under Article 21."
      },
      {
        "title": "Mandamus for Police Protection",
        "content": "The Court issued a writ of mandamus directing the relevant district police to provide protection to the petitioners, ensuring their safety without interference from private respondents."
      },
      {
        "title": "Conclusion – Personal Autonomy and Constitutional Rights",
        "content": "The Court reaffirmed that the choice of a partner, regardless of religious affiliation, is an intrinsic component of personal liberty, and any state interference must be justified under constitutional safeguards."
      }
    ],
